<HEADLINE> Nepali Opposition Party Threatens to Withdraw Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The main opposition party of
Nepal said Monday that if the present minority government does not
heed the national issues and its demands, it will have to withdraw
its support, which is crucial for the survival of the government.
</P>
<P>
Man Mohan Adhikari, chairman of the Communist Party of Nepal
(United Marxism-Leninism) (CPN-UML), made the threat at a press
conference following a similar one by his party on Sunday at the
opening session of parliament.
</P>
<P>
He alleged that the government under the slogan of seeking
national consensus has not done anything and has tried to suppress
the people.
</P>
<P>
He said India has encroached upon the Nepalese territory
including Pashupatinagar in eastern Nepal and Kalapani in the
far-western part of the country and has stationed its army in
Kalapani, but the government has not taken the issue seriously.
</P>
<P>
Besides, a review of the 1950 Peace and Friendship Treaty
between the two countries as raised by his party has not moved
forward, he said.
</P>
<P>
And the policies adopted by the government in the economic
sector made the economic situation worse, he claimed.
</P>
<P>
"If the government does not pay proper attention to the
national issues and our demands, we may be compelled to withdraw
our support," he warned.
</P>
<P>
After assuming power in mid-April, the government led by Girija
Prasad Koirala survived a vote of confidence with the support of
the CPN-UML, which however presented a 36-point demand as a
precondition.
</P>
<P>
At the opening session of parliament on Sunday, the CPN-UML
indicated that it may withdraw its support if the government does
not heed the national problems.
</P>
<P>
At the session, other opposition parties also strongly
criticized the government over the issue of Kalapani and other
issues.
</P>
<P>
Koirala is to face a tough time as the summer session, also
known as the budget session, will discuss and pass the budget
presented by his government for the 1998/99 fiscal year which
begins in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
If he fails to muster 103 votes for the passage of the budget
in the 205-seat Lower House, where his Nepali Congress Party holds
only 88 seats, he has no other choice but to resign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
