<HEADLINE> Water Pollution in China Serious, Top Legislator Says (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Analyzing the causes of water shortages, Zou said that
pollution has greatly reduced the use of water resources, damaged
the environment affecting water, lowered the effective supply of
water resources, and threatened people's safe drinking water
supply.
</P>
<P>
Zou said water pollution in China is so serious that the speed
of treatment can't keep up with the increase in pollution. Water
pollution is expanding from the urban areas to rural areas and
from parts of a river to the whole basin, he said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the country's rivers and lakes and coastal seas are
polluted to differing degrees, and the quality of the water
environment is continuing to be degraded, Zou said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, water quality of major rivers declined in all the
basins of the country, and the pollution of rivers in the north
part of China has become more critical than that in the south,
according to a study by the research center under the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The study shows that water pollution worsened last year in the
coastal areas and in the river sections that pass through
cities. Some 80 percent of the water of the Yellow River, China's
second largest river, is polluted, it states.
</P>
<P>
Qu Geping, chairman of the NPC Environmental and Resources
Protection Committee, also spoke at the meeting, saying that the
water pollution law has played an active role in increased
treatment and in improving the water environment.
</P>
<P>
But, Qu said, it should be noted that the water environment is
not good, with the total drainage of wastewater going up and the
polluted areas expanding.
</P>
<P>
The domestic sewage in urban areas has doubled compared with
1990, increasing by up to 19 billion tons yearly, with an annual
increase of 12.7 percent, Qu said.
</P>
<P>
However, the rate of sewage treatment is only about 13.6
percent, that is, some 16 billion tons of sewage was directly
poured into rivers and lakes, Qu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
