<HEADLINE> 3 Chinese Cities Among World's Five Costliest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Three Chinese cities, Hong Kong,
Beijing and Shanghai have been rated among the five most expensive
cities in the world in the spring of 1998, with Tokyo, Japan, and
Moscow, Russia, coming second and the fourth respectively.
</P>
<P>
"The trend during the past 12 months indicates that Chinese
cities are tending to become more expensive despite inflation
rates approaching zero percent," said the Geneva-based Corporate
Resources Group (CRG). The Group published its spring 1998 edition
of the Worldwide Cost of Living Rankings here Monday.
</P>
<P>
China's Guangzhou (seventh) and Dalian (ninth) are among the
top ten and Shenzhen is 11th.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the CRG said, Japanese cities are becoming less
expensive as the yen weakens. Tokyo has fallen from first place in
the previous year to second. Osaka (sixth) is the only Japanese
city in the top ten besides Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
South East Asian cities have dropped dramatically as the
financial crisis in the region takes its toll. Seoul, South Korea,
fell from seventh in 1997 to the 46th in 1998 and Singapore fell
from the eighth to the 13th.
</P>
<P>
Swiss cities Geneva and Zurich, not so long ago among the top
five cities, continue to fall in the world rankings. Geneva and
Zurich are now ranked 17th and 18th in the world, nearly on the
same level as New York (21st).
</P>
<P>
With New York as the base of 100 index points, Hong Kong, the
world's most expensive city with an index of 157.4, is 266 percent
more expensive than Harare (150th), the capital of Zimbabwe, and
now the world's least expensive city with an index of 43.0.
</P>
<P>
The gap between the most expensive and the least expensive
cities has widened slightly to 114 index points compared to 110
points one year ago.
</P>
<P>
Affecting the ranking in the cost of living are more than 200
issues involving costs in ten categories including food at home,
alcohol and tobacco, domestic spending, personal care, clothes and
footwear, home services, utilities like energy costs and telephone
charges, entertainment, transport, and sports and leisure.
</P>
<P>
Moscow remains Europe's most expensive city. New York is the
most expensive city in North America. Sao Paulo, Brazil, is the
most expensive city in South America. Luanda, the capital of
Angola is the most expensive city in Africa. Tel Aviv, Israel,
remains the most expensive city in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The top ten cities with their index points are Hong Kong
(157.40), Tokyo (154.30), Beijing (153.10), Moscow (151.30),
Shanghai (144.90), Osaka (140.90), Guangzhou (122.80),
St. Petersburg (115.10), Dalian (112.90) and London (111.60).
</P>
</TEXT>
