<HEADLINE> U.S. New Home Sales Go Up to Record High in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. nationwide sales of
new homes rose 0.3 percent to a record in May, the Commerce
Department reported here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sales reached a seasonally-adjusted annual rate of 890,000 last
month, the highest since the government began tracking them in
1963, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
May is also the ninth consecutive month of sales at or above
800,000, the longest such streak in 21 years. For the first five
months of the year, sales were 8.8 percent higher than the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Home sales which include both new and existing, have been
exceptionally strong this year, largely attributed to the lowest
unemployment rates and close to the lowest mortgage interest rates
in nearly 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, sales were strongest in the West in May, jumping
15.7 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 265,000, the
most since September 1979. They climbed 3.3 percent in the
Northeast to a rate of 94,000, highest in 14 months.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, the strong sales helped hold down the inventory of
unsold homes. They totaled 289,000, a 3.9-month supply at the
current sales pace, the same as the month before.
</P>
<P>
The median price of a new home was 149,900 dollars in May, up
6.3 percent from a year ago.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
