<HEADLINE> Annan's Envoy Delivers Message to Pakistani PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Alvaro De Soto, special envoy of
United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Monday met Pakistani
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and delivered a letter from the U.N.
chief.
</P>
<P>
De Soto conveyed to Sharif the "continuing concern" of Annan
over the situation in South Asia and the importance of finding
ways of defusing tension and addressing its root causes, according
to the official Associated Press of Pakistan (APP).
</P>
<P>
Sharif expressed his appreciation for the efforts initiated by
Annan, and called on the U.N. to encourage, facilitate and support
a credible process of peace and rapprochement in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Sharif also underscored the need for the U.N. to take effective
steps for the implementation of U.N. Security Council resolutions
on Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
He further drew attention to the precarious situation created
by "Indian violations" of the Line of Control.
</P>
<P>
It was imperative that the U.N. discharge its responsibilities
for the preservation and maintenance of international peace and
security, he said.
</P>
<P>
He told De Soto that he was prepared to meet the Indian prime
minister in Colombo, Sri Lanka, next month and also renewed his
invitation to the U.N. secretary-general to visit Islamabad as
soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
