<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana to Retain Rand Peg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Botswana's central bank said
Monday there are no plans to scrap the de facto pegging of the
Pula to the South African Rand despite the severe impact of the
tumbling Rand to the Botswanan economy.
</P>
<P>
The falling South African currency has pulled the Pula down
almost 16 percent against the U.S. Dollar and Pound Sterling over
12 months. Pula stood at 0.2349 U.S. Dollars or 0.1410 Pounds
Sterling last Friday, compared to 0.2783 U.S. Dollars and 0.1673
Pounds a year ago.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot say how far we will go. When the Rand is under
great pressure, we watch the situation carefully," Governor
Baledzi Gaolathe was quoted by South African Press Association as
saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Pula is believed to be pegged to a basket of six
currencies. The central bank would not give details of the
basket's makeup, but market sources say that the Rand comprises
60 percent of the basket's weight.
</P>
<P>
This is to protect Botswana's fledgling manufacturing
industries, which are central to the diversification of the
economy from its dependence on diamond revenues. Eighty percent
of Botswana's non-diamond exports go to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
There has been an apparent lessening of the weight of the Rand
in the basket over the 12 months. The Pula has shown an
appreciation of 7.4 percent from 1.2586 Rand in June 1997 to
1.3522 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Botswana stockbrokers have voiced their fears that the falling
Pula will adversely affect the fortunes of the Botswana Stock
Exchange, which has so far avoided the storm blowing over the
emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
"There could be increased off-loading of stocks...I think we
are starting to see that already," Chief Executive of
Stockbrokers Botswana said.
</P>
<P>
Some said that the market is getting close to the point where
investors would forget the underlying strength of Botswana's
economy and see only a weakening currency, triggering massive
capital outflow.
</P>
<P>
Botswana has the world's fastest growing economy in the past
three decades, a World Bank report said earlier this year. The
country's growth rates in recent years were above six percent,
much better than the southern African and continental average.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
