<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Chirac's Quiet But Important Visit to S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- In contrast to U.S.
President Bill Clinton's lavish show in South Africa three months
ago, French President Jacques Chirac's visit to the country
seemed to be quiet.
</P>
<P>
But the three-day state visit which ended Sunday is no less
important than Clinton's, observers believe.
</P>
<P>
It is well known that Chirac's visit is aimed at spreading his
country's economic and political influence southward from the
Francophone Africa.
</P>
<P>
France, like other big powers, considers South Africa as its
best new partner in Africa. South Africa, which produces about
30 percent of Africa's wealth, is rising as the leader in the
emerging markets in the continent.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is France's largest trading partner in the
sub-Saharan Africa and their bilateral trade has doubled since
1994, with the balance much in France's favor.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral trade between France and South Africa amounted
to about 6.6 billion Rand (about 1.3 billion U.S. Dollars) in
1997, a 20.5 percent increase from 1996.
</P>
<P>
The new French companies in South Africa have trebled in
number over the past four years and there are now about 130
established French companies in the country.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, France is now only South Africa's 11th biggest
trading partner, lagging behind South Africa's three main trading
partners, Britain, Germany and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Franco-South African Economic Forum on Friday,
Chirac lamented his country's weak image in the southern Africa
and called for efforts to promote the economic cooperation
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that France is ready to play a bigger role in South
Africa's economy.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the trade between South Africa and the rest of the
continent has doubled since 1994, Chirac said fears that France
and South Africa would become rivals are not founded.
</P>
<P>
The French president said that the two countries, instead of
competing, complement each other in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Firstly, because South Africa's areas of excellence in Africa
differ significantly from ours; secondly, because our
geographical focus differs, France's position is especially in
north and west Africa. South Africa continues to focus primarily
on southern Africa, which accounts for two-thirds of its African
exports, and to a lesser extent, on the east Africa."
</P>
<P>
South Africa, on the other hand, is no less enthusiastic about
forging closer ties with France.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's ambition to play a crucial role in Africa and
to be a major player in the international community could not be
achieved without the support of France, which is a permanent
member of the United Nations Security Council and a leading
member of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said Friday that Chirac's visit was of great importance
to South Africa. "It is quite clear that, as we try to improve
ourselves as a country and try to play a new role in the world,
we will need the friendship and support of France."
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Chirac promised South Africa with new
investments, a free trade agreement between South Africa and the
European Union before the end of the year and France's support
for South Africa's bid for a permanent seat in the U.N. Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
As another gesture which will certainly win support from
African countries, Chirac made it clear that his country favors
debt relief for poor countries.
</P>
<P>
His stand was in sharp contrast to Washington's new
trade-for-aid Africa policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Legislature Approves 1998 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian Legislative
Council (PLC) approved Monday the 1998 budget of about 1.8 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The 88-member PLC passed the budget in a special session held
in the West Bank city Ramallah, the East Jerusalem-based
Palestinian news service the Jerusalem Media and Communication
Center (JMCC) reported.
</P>
<P>
The vote was 37-22 with six abstentions, and 23 PLC
members did not attend the session.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 budget totaled 1.85 billion dollars with a deficit of
36.9 million dollars. Of the budget, about 900 million dollars are
foreign aid that will be allocated for development projects, the
JMCC said.
</P>
<P>
Some amendments have been made to the original budget plan
presented by the Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Early this month, some PLC members cited the unreasonable
budget allocations as one of the reasons for threatening to file a
no-confidence motion against the PNA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
