<HEADLINE> UK Bankruptcies Up As Jobs Dwindle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The number of business failures in
Britain jumped by nearly 10 percent in the second quarter of the
year, providing firm evidence that the manufacturing sector is
heading for recession.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 businesses failed in April-June, 4 percent
higher than a year earlier, according to a quarterly survey
conducted by Dun &AMP; Bradstreet published Monday.
</P>
<P>
It also warned that the number of business failures in five
figures was the first time in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
"There are worrying signs in these latest figures which will
need to be checked during the rest of the year," said Dun &AMP;
Bradstreet senior analyst Philip Mellor.
</P>
<P>
Separate employment statistics, also published Monday, showed
that pressures on the labor market may be beginning to ease.
</P>
<P>
The Manpower third-quarter survey of employment prospects
revealed that there was no acceleration in labor market growth
compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Manpower research, which surveyed 2,221 employers, said
that 28 percent of employers predict an increase in job levels for
the three months from July to September, but 8 percent reckon
there will be a decline.
</P>
<P>
The balance of 20 percent is equal to the figure for the third
quarter last year. It is the first time since 1996 that a
quarter's result has shown no improvement over the year before.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts here believe that the two sets of data are
likely to add to pressure on the Bank of England not to make a
further rate rise when it meets early next month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
