<HEADLINE> Ethiopians Urged to Pay Due Attention to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Vice Minister
of Health Monday urged the people in the country to pay due
attention to the problem of blindness.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting here, Vice Minister Lamisso Hayesso said
that nearly 900,000 people in Ethiopia suffer from blindness
mainly caused by trachoma and cataract.
</P>
<P>
The vice minister said that about 90 percent of blindness in
Ethiopia is preventable.
</P>
<P>
The number of blind people worldwide is estimated to be about
45 million, Lamisso said, adding that the prevalence of blindness
is 10 to 20 times greater in the developing countries compared
with that in the developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion, Regional Representative of
Christoffel Blinden Mission in Ethiopia M. Spath said that
Ethiopia has been selected as one of the 16 priority countries
worldwide where national trachoma control programs would be
implemented.
</P>
<P>
He added that 50 to 75 percent of blind people in Ethiopia
could be cured with the availability of the necessary facilities
for eye care, trained personnel and a concept for primary eye
care programs.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry of health, a blindness prevention
team has been established under the ministry to implement the
trachoma control program in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
