<HEADLINE> Russian Ambassador to Belarus Leaves Drozdy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Russian Ambassador to Belarus
Valery Loshchinin has left his residence in the Drozdy complex
outside Minsk, capital of Belarus, to a city apartment, Russian
Foreign Ministry's spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador sealed his residence in the Drozdy complex
because electricity and water there had been cut off, the Interfax
news agency quoted Rakhmanin as saying.
</P>
<P>
Loshchinin reminded the Minsk's side of that his residence in
Drozdy by an agreement between Russia and Belarus is Russia's
property.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he noted that Moscow has no plan to recall its
ambassador from Minsk.
</P>
<P>
In later April, the Belarussian authorities notified more than
20 ambassadors who lived in the Drozdy residences to move out of
there to allow a renovation work.
</P>
<P>
These ambassadors accused Minsk of violating the Vienna
Convention on diplomatic rights and ambassadors from Britain,
France, Germany, Greece, Italy and the United States and other
states have left the Drozdy residences.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Rakhmanin at a briefing described the Belarussian
authorities' move as "an undiplomatic act", and on behalf of the
Russian side expressed regret about the conflict over the Drozdy
complex and about the departure of individual ambassadors from
Belarus.
</P>
<P>
The Russian spokesman said the Russian side had done everything
it could to prevent the aggravation of this conflict and to settle
it through talks.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the problem will be solved with due
account taken of the interests of all sides.  
</P>
