<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Inflation Rate Continues to Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's inflation rate
declined from 13.2 percent in April to 12.6 percent last month
due to decrease in prices of basic foodstuffs.
</P>
<P>
According to the monthly economic review report issued by the
Bank of Tanzania made available Monday, the overall inflation
rate which started to decline last September, continued to fall
last month.
</P>
<P>
The report said the inflation rate on underlying basis --
excluding food prices, dropped from 7.1 percent in April to 6.6
percent in May. This was mainly due to the low increase of costs
of key non-food items, such as fuel, power, water and
transportation, as well as rents.
</P>
<P>
The trend of decline in inflation is expected to continue in
the months ahead due to increased food supplies and continuation
of tight fiscal and monetary policies, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Government revenue collection in May stood at 49.9 billion
Shillings (about 75 million U.S. Dollars) against the targeted
52.6 billion Shillings. The collection in May was 1.6 billion
Shillings less than the amount of the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the government spent 70.5 billion Shillings, a
91.2 percent of the monthly estimated expenditure. However, the
May expenditure hit the highest level since last July, the
beginning of the 1997/98 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
At the end of May, grain procurement remained at 40,000 tons,
a 70.2 percent of the targeted 57,000 tons for this season.
</P>
<P>
The report forecast enough food production for this season.
The production is estimated at 7.8 million tons, up 34.5 percent
over the output of last season.
</P>
<P>
Production of cereals is expected to increase from three
million tons in 1996/97 fiscal year to about 4.5 million tons in
1997/98. Meanwhile, non-cereals are expected to increase from 2.8
million tons last year to 3.3 million tons this year.
</P>
<P>
Export earnings declined to 44.1 million U.S. Dollars last
month, compared to 44.5 million U.S. Dollars in April, while
imports bill increased to 128.5 million U.S. Dollars last month
from 119.5 million U.S. Dollars in the previous month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
