<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Welcomes Gulf Arab States' Readiness to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Iran Monday expressed welcome to
the readiness of Gulf Arab states to expand relations with Tehran,
but reiterating its sovereignty over three disputed Gulf islands.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on a communique of the Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC), Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi said
that Iran's firm principle is to strengthen and expand ties with
neighboring Muslim countries, Gulf Arab states in particular.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of GCC members said in the communique
issued at the end of their 67th meeting Sunday in Saudi Arabia
that GCC states are willing to promote ties with Iran.
</P>
<P>
GCC, a regional political and economic alliance, groups six
Arab countries of Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and
the United Arab Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said that developing and deepening cooperation among
regional countries would be the only way to maintain stability and
security in the strategic Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
Iran believes that mutual understanding, dialog, promotion of
cooperation would help develop and promote relations, remove
misunderstandings and strengthen mutual trust among the regional
countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mohammadi stressed that the islands of Abu Musa, the
Greater and Less Tunbs in the Gulf are "inseparable parts of Iran."
</P>
<P>
The only way to solve the problem between Iran and the UAE is
mutual understanding and bilateral talks.
</P>
<P>
The GCC countries have expressed hope that the talks between
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi and UAE officials in Abu
Dhabi last month would lead to a "favorable response from Tehran
to Abu Dhabi's initiatives aimed at a peaceful solution to their
territorial disputes."
</P>
<P>
After the British forces withdrew from the region in 1971,
Iran took over the three islands at the mouth of the strategic
Hormuz Strait. But the UAE also claimed sovereignty over the
islands.
</P>
<P>
During Kharrazi's visit, the two countries agreed to solve
their disputes through peaceful means. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
