<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) Administrator James Gustave Speth has called the
drop in development aid by developed nations as a tragedy, a UNDP
publication reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Western societies will pay dearly for their present-day neglect
of the problems of the developing world, the weekly UNDP Flash
quoted Speth as telling journalists in Dublin, Ireland, last week.
</P>
<P>
Against the background of international aid falling for the
fifth straight year in 1997, Speth said it is a tragedy that aid
spending is plunging just when it is needed the most.
</P>
<P>
The aid decrease will cost the world more later in terms of
humanitarian assistance, peace-keeping and fight against diseases,
drugs and terrorism, Speth warned. 
</P>
