<HEADLINE> Nigeria Waiting for UN Chief: Foreign Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan will arrive in Nigeria later Monday for a four-day
official visit, according to the foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a statement Monday in the capital Abuja
that during the visit, Annan would meet with the head of state,
General Abdulsalam Abubakar, to discuss issues of common interest
to the U.N. and Nigeria, including the maintenance of
sub-regional peace and security.
</P>
<P>
"The government and people of Nigeria look forward to the
visit of the secretary-general and to its successful outcome," it
added.
</P>
<P>
Annan's visit to Nigeria is one in a series done by
high-ranking figures recently as part of the efforts by the West
to restore democracy in the west African country.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Office Minister Tony Lloyd paid a visit to
Nigeria last week on behalf of the European Union. The
secretary-general of the Commonwealth, Chief Emeka Anyaoku, who
is from Nigeria, is in the country.
</P>
<P>
These visits are also expected to help break the diplomatic
isolation Nigeria has been faced with since 1993 when the Western
world imposed sanctions on the country.
</P>
<P>
The West has seen the sudden death of Nigeria's former
military leader General Sani Abacha as an opportunity to improve
relations with the most populous black African country.
</P>
<P>
Western countries hope Abacha's successor, General Abubakar
would handle the military government's transition to civil rule
program in a way that would bring democracy to the country.
</P>
