<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Condemns Netanyahu's Call for Madrid II </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Foreign Minister Jawad
Anani denounced Monday Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
call for convening a second international meeting to discuss the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released here, Anani said Jordan rejects the
convening of such a meeting because Netanyahu is trying to evade
Israel's commitments to the Oslo accords that it signed with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He believed that Netanyahu's idea of reviving the multilateral
negotiations within a new framework will not be accepted by most
of the Arab states.
</P>
<P>
Jordan thinks that what Netanyahu should do at the present
time is to carry out his pledges made under the signed peace
accords and restart negotiations with the concerned parties, he
added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that in addition to the Oslo accords and the 1997
Hebron agreement, there also some existing resolutions adopted by
the United Nations Security Council concerning the Israeli-Arab
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"If Netanyahu wants peace, then the solutions are there.
The only thing he has to do is to agree on them," said
Anani.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Netanyahu proposed to convene an international
conference following the example of the 1991 Madrid conference to
discuss the peace process as well as regional issues in the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
But his proposal sparked widespread condemnation from the
Palestinians, Arabs and other countries, which denounced it as an
attempt to escape from fulfilling Israeli commitments.
</P>
<P>
The 1991 Madrid conference, which brought the Israelis and
Arabs to face-to-face talks for the first time, set the framework
for the subsequent peace talks between Israel and its Arab
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Little progress has been achieved in the Mideast peace process
since mid-1996 when the Netanyahu-led rightwing government came to
power.
</P>
<P>
Israel's talks with Syria and Lebanon have not resumed so far,
while the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have been stalled since
early last year due to Israel's refusal to carry out the long
overdue troop redeployment in the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
