<HEADLINE> Angola to Be in National Mourning for Late UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government decided
Monday to go into a 48-hour national mourning for the late United
Nations special representative to Angola, Alioune Blondin Beye.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government announced the decree here Monday,
saying that during the mourning period, governments at all levels
should fly the flag at half-mast.
</P>
<P>
Beye was confirmed dead in a plane crash near the commercial
capital Abidjan of Cote d'Ivoire. All on board including the two
crew of the South African Beechcraft 200 and five members of the
U.N. observer mission in Angola died in the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Beye was on a shuttle mission to Sao Tome and Principe, Gabon,
Togo, Cote d'Ivoire and Burkina Faso to drum up support for a bid
to avert renewed bloodshed in war-ravaged Angola where he had
been the special representative since 1993.
</P>
<P>
The delegation of the Angolan government led by Minister of
Territorial Administer Faustino Muteka left Monday for Malian
capital Bamako to attend the burial of the late former Malian
foreign minister who had made great contribution to the Angolan
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the Angolan political parties agreed that
Africa has lost one of the "distinguished sons," saying that Beye
had made great efforts to the complicated peace process in the
southern African country.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the predecessor of Beye, Magaret Anstee
who had been U.N. Special Representative to Angola between 1991
and 1993, said in New York Monday that the passing away of Beye
dealt a "serious hit" to the Angolan peace process.
</P>
<P>
Nontheless, Anstee expressed her hope that the 1994 Lusaka
Peace Protocol will be fully implemented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
