<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iowa Governor's Race Already Running Hot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The candidates for governor of
Iowa, the United States, have already begun tearing into each
other shortly after the June primary.
</P>
<P>
Attack commercials are already flying, the candidates are
trading charges of illegal campaign cash, and the rhetoric has
escalated to levels usually reserved for late October, the
Associated Press reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The presidential nominating season in the United States begins
with Iowa's precinct caucuses, so whoever is elected the next
governor will instantly become a power broker.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time the governor's seat has been open in 16
years. Republican Governor Terry Branstad, first elected in 1982,
is stepping down.
</P>
<P>
"There's so much at stake," the report quoted Iowa Republican
chairman Steve Grubbs as saying. "There's nothing in Iowa politics
more important than an open governor's seat -- ever."
</P>
<P>
Democratic operative Phil Roeder said, "With the first open
seat in the better part of two decades, it should start off hot
and heavy."
</P>
<P>
The early favorite is Republican Jim Ross Lightfoot, who was in
Congress for a dozen years before losing a Senate race two years
ago. Lightfoot, 59, will face state Senator Tom Vilsack, a lawyer
who narrowly won the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
Trailing in the early polls, Vilsack, 47, has wasted absolutely
no time launching his campaign. He has ripped into Lightfoot as a
tool of Big Tobacco, and a political action committee created by
Democratic Senator Tom Harkin has begun airing commercials bashing
Lightfoot.
</P>
<P>
"It's just the nature of politics today," said former Iowa
Democratic chairman Eric Tabor. "There's more money and you have
to either define yourself or define your opponent early on. Both
parties understand there's a lot at stake."
</P>
<P>
Lightfoot has hired Steve Griener, a former top aide to House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, to run his campaign. Lightfoot, a
Republican conservative, picked in the June primary as his running
mate Almo Hawkins, a black woman and former TV reporter. Ms.
Hawkins has been head of the state's Department of Human Rights
for 15 years, working as an advocate for women, minorities and the
disabled.
</P>
<P>
Although minorities represent just three percent of Iowa's
population, Republican strategists say that Ms. Hawkins can lure
some of those Democratic-leaning voters into their camp.
</P>
<P>
Democrats say that Lightfoot is a harsh conservative who won't
be able to stand up under the spotlight of a gubernatorial
campaign.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Al Gore, House Democratic leader Richard
Gephardt and Minnesota Senator Paul Wellstone are all scheduled to
campaign for Vilsack this summer. Jesse Jackson has already made
an appearance.
</P>
<P>
When Republicans held their state convention, 10 potential
candidates found time in their schedule to attend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
