<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU FMs Approve Strategic Partnership With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- European Union foreign ministers
approved Monday the European Commission's new strategy toward
China.
</P>
<P>
The approval, made during a foreign ministers council meeting
in Luxembourg, provides for closer engagement and cooperation
between China and the 15-nation union.
</P>
<P>
The new European Commission strategy includes concrete measures
to support China's economic integration into the global economy,
to reinforce its economic and social reforms and to encourage its
development into a more open society based on the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
One concrete measure was the commission proposal to elevate the
EU-China relationship to presidential level that is expected to
take effect in late October this year when European Commission
President Jacques Santer visits China, commission officials said.
</P>
<P>
The key of the new policy, the officials added, is to focus,
through trade negotiations, political dialogue, human rights and
economic cooperation, on the single goal of assisting China in
building a globally competitive economy serving a free and open
society based on the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
European Commission Vice-President Sir Leon Brittan said, "This
new policy now sends an important further signal to the Chinese
leadership: the realization of China's potential as a leading
power in Asia over the long term will hinge on its ability to
match its domestic reforms with a commitment to open markets on a
world scale."
</P>
<P>
He pledged that with this policy endorsed by the governments of
the 15 EU member states, the European Union is to support the
internal reform and external liberalization in China.
</P>
<P>
"The world will gain from China's development into an open and
prosperous society and an equal partner in the world economy.
Europe must now work to strengthen its economic partnership with
China," the commission vice-president said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
