<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli President Causes Controversy by Calling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman
caused a political storm in Israel's Knesset (Parliament) Monday
by calling for early general elections.
</P>
<P>
Knesset members reacted to the president's remarks following
party lines, with the left-wingers expressing support while the
right-wingers criticizing him of intervening politics.
</P>
<P>
Labor Party leader Ehud Barak, who has called for early
elections himself recently, said that if anyone goes to the
streets of Tel Aviv or Jerusalem, he will find that people are
thinking in the same way as what Weizman has said.
</P>
<P>
He refused to comment if the president's words have constituted
an intervention in the politics, saying that Weizman was "saying
what he feels."
</P>
<P>
During a condolence visit Monday to the family of Orr Cohen, a
soldier killed last week in south Lebanon, Weizman said that since
the peace process is limping along, the best thing to do now is to
organize general elections.
</P>
<P>
Several cabinet ministers quickly responded by criticizing him
of taking sides with the left-wing parties by making the remarks.
</P>
<P>
In the Knesset, Likud member Naomi Blumenthal said that "it is
not right" for the president to intervene in a role that he was
not voted to play.
</P>
<P>
Another Likud member Uzi Landau said the president should play
a role above day-to-day politics.
</P>
<P>
But Labor Knesset member Haggai Merom dismissed the complaints
as "hypocritical."
</P>
<P>
The president was "just saying the truth" and people have to
accept Weizman "as a political president," he said.
</P>
<P>
With his words and manner getting him in hot water time and
again, Weizman has recently been more critical of the impasse in
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In a surprise move last week, he did not speak at an economic
conference in Israel as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
"I reached a conclusion that if I speak, it would be an angry
speech," he explained.
</P>
<P>
The president said that he was disappointed with the fact that
a decision by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on further
withdrawal from the West Bank "is not near."
</P>
<P>
Although the post of the Israeli president is ceremonial,
people believe that Weizman's words carry a certain weight.
</P>
<P>
Avoiding a direct comment, Netanyahu said on Monday that no
pressure or individual will steer him away from "pursuing a true
peace" with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Once again, he blamed the Palestinians for the stalemate of the
peace process, saying the main thing now holding up progress is
Palestinians' refusal to honor their commitments they have made in
the signed agreements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
