<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Africa Joins UN Weapons Protocols </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has joined two
United Nations weapons protocols which prohibit or restrict the
use of land mines, booby-traps and blinding laser weapons.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has declared its consent to be bound to the
amended protocol II and IV of the Convention on Prohibitions or
Restrictions on the Use of Certain Conventional Weapons, the
Foreign Ministry said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The declaration was deposited at the U.N. Secretary-General's
office in New York, the United States, on June 26, the ministry
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Certain conventional weapons, or CCW, are weapons deemed to be
excessively injurious or to have indiscriminate effects.
</P>
<P>
South Africa acceded to the convention and its protocols I, II
and III in September 1995. The convention, which came into force
in December 1983, has to date been ratified by 70 states.
</P>
<P>
The amended protocol II, adopted in May 1996, requires greater
discrimination between civilian and military objectives requiring
advance warning of mines, booby-traps and other devices.
</P>
<P>
The new protocol IV, adopted by state parties in October 1995,
places a prohibition on the use of blinding laser weapons
designed to cause blindness.
</P>
<P>
In another statement on Monday, the ministry said that South
Africa has also agreed to ratify the Convention on the
Prohibition of the Use, Stockpiling, Production and Transfer of
Anti-Personnel Mines, and on Their Destruction.
</P>
<P>
This followed the earlier ratification of the convention by
the South African parliament in May 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
