<HEADLINE> Blair, Ahern Meet on Ulster March Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
and his Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern, held emergency talks on
Tuesday to discuss the security implications of an attempt to
limit a Protestant march this weekend.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman said the two leaders agreed that
"everyone in positions of responsibility must do all they can to
ensure that it passes off peacefully."
</P>
<P>
The leaders held talks for 20 minutes in Frankfurt to discuss
the Northern Ireland peace process. The talks preceded an EU
meeting to mark the launch of the European Central Bank, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland is bracing itself for possible sectarian
street violence at the parade on Sunday. The Protestant marchers
have been barred from a Roman Catholic enclave in Drumcree, close
to the strongly pro-British town of Portadown. But they vowed on
Monday to continue their marches as planned.
</P>
<P>
The parade by the Orange Order, viewed by Northern Ireland's
Catholic minority as a threatening expression of Protestant
triumphalism, touched off rioting across the province in 1996 and
1997.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the two leaders also expressed their
confidence in the new Northern Ireland Assembly which was elected
last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Both saw the (assembly) elections as a further significant
step towards the new politics the people want. Both are confident
the assembly can and will work," the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
