<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Confidence Rises to 29-Year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. consumers' confidence in
the economy rose in June to a 29-year high, as Americans remained
optimistic about the labor market and economic growth in coming
months.
</P>
<P>
The New York based Conference Board reported Tuesday that its
index of consumer confidence rose from a revised 136.3 in May to
137.6 in June, a rise larger than Wall Street had expected.
</P>
<P>
June's gain pushed the index above the 29-year high of 137.4 set
in February. In June 1969, the index once reached 137.9.
</P>
<P>
Economists regard the consumer sentiment as important because
consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of the nation's overall
economic activity.
</P>
<P>
The report comes as economists look for new data for signs
pointing to the direction of the economy and any inflationary
pressures and as Federal Reserve begins two days of meetings in
Washington to review interest rate policy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
