<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA to Impose Lockout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- With negotiations on a new
labor agreement at a standstill, the National Basketball
Association announced on Monday that it would lock out its players
Tuesday night until a new collective bargaining agreement is
reached.
</P>
<P>
The lockout will, in essence, shut down the league. Teams will
be barred from talking to their players, trades and free agent
signings will be prohibited and summer leagues will be canceled.
</P>
<P>
"The expired collective bargaining agreement between the NBA
and its players did not work." said NBA Deputy Commissioner Russ
Granik.
</P>
<P>
"That agreement guaranteed the players at least 48% of league
revenue. The parties expressly agreed that the deal was not
working if player compensation exceed 52%. The past season players
compensation exceeded 57%."
</P>
<P>
"We have made a series of proposals to the players under which
salaries would continue to increase - but at a slower rate than
under the expired deal," Granik said. "Regrettably, the players
have rejected all of these proposals. The NBA will not operate
until we reach a new agreement that is fair to both parties."
</P>
<P>
This will be third lockout in the history of the NBA, the only
major American professional sports league never to have lost a
game to a work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
A lockout in the summer of 1995 lasted three months, and a
lockout in 1996 lasted only a couple of hours.
</P>
<P>
A handful of players who were to be paid part of their salaries
this summer will not receive those paychecks until the lockout
ends.
</P>
<P>
Also, teams will not be permitted to conduct practices, summer
camps, workouts, coaching sessions or team meetings. Some
previously scheduled charity games will be allowed to proceed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women Surpass Men in Schooling in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Young women in the United
States are completing high school and graduating from college at
higher rates than their male peers, according to the Census
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said in a report Monday that in 1997, 89 percent of
women ages 25 to 29 had finished high school, compared with 86
percent of men the same age.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times quoted census officials as saying that women
in the 25 to 29 age group also led men when it came to college
completion rates: 29.3 percent for women, compared with 26.3
percent for men in 1997.
</P>
<P>
It was the second year that young women had outpaced men in
education attainment. In 1996, women topped men 28.2 percent to
26.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
On the performance, the bureau found that there was almost
indistinguishable when it came to finishing high school or
completing college in the 10-year period before 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, in the last two years, young women have spurted ahead,
the first time in the America's history that women are better
educated than their male counterpart.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the trend, the Census Bureau said that more women
are delaying both marriage and childbirth, two events that
traditionally have caused women to halt their education. In
addition, social attitudes have changed drastically with regard to
women earning college degrees and entering the professional work
force.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, large-scale U.S. military action that usually pushed
up male school enrollment has been largely absent in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also show that young blacks have almost caught
up with whites in the percentage graduating from high school, 86
percent of blacks age 25 to 29 were high school graduate in last
year, compared to 87 percent of whites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
