<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Marks Founding of European Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FRANKFURT, Germany, June 30 (Xinhua) -- European Union states
held an official ceremony here Tuesday to mark the founding of the
European Central Bank (ECB).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony at the Old Opera House of Frankfurt,
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl described the establishment of the
ECB as "an important milestone in the history of the European
integration."
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that under the guidance of the European
Central Bank, the planned single European currency, the euro,
which is to be launched on January 1, 1999, was set to be a great
success like the German mark.
</P>
<P>
The ECB was formally established on June 1, and will act as the
monetary watchdog for the euro. It will set the common monetary
policy and common interest rates for all 11 EU countries which
participate in the first wave of the euro introduction next
January.
</P>
<P>
Also addressing the ceremony, ECB President Wim Duisenberg said
that by fulfilling its mandate of maintaining price stability, the
ECB would contribute to creating the appropriate conditions for
sustainable growth of incomes and employment in the euro area.
</P>
<P>
However, he also stressed that the new central bank would have
to first face the most important challenge, to win public trust.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony on Tuesday was attended by hundreds of European
political and business leaders including European Commission
President Jacques Santer, British Prime Minister Tony Blair,
Austrian Chancellor Viktor Klima, and the central bank governors
of EU countries.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at the event, Santer noted that the ECB would
face the big challenge of building authority by ensuring a stable
common currency for EU countries in the long run.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that with the establishment of the ECB and
planned launch of the euro, European countries must get ready to
take new international responsibilities to cope with challenges
such as the recent Asian financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
