<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Firms Rush to File Year 2000 Responses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Australia's public
companies Tuesday rushed to lodge their compliance responses on
the Year 2000 bug with the Australian Stock Exchange (ASX) before
Tuesday night's deadline.
</P>
<P>
But some companies appeared prepared to gamble by forgoing
compliance costs and risking litigation in some areas of their
business.
</P>
<P>
The deadline set by the ASX for disclosure of compliance was at
8 p.m. (local time) Tuesday. But by 7 p.m. about 105 of
Australia's public companies had still to respond to the ASX's
demand.
</P>
<P>
Under the listing laws, the ASX requires all public companies
to provide information about the status of their Year 2000 bug
projects.
</P>
<P>
In a last-minute dash Tuesday, about 370 Australian companies
swamped the ASX in Sydney with their notices, the largest number
in any single day.
</P>
<P>
By 6 p.m. Tuesday, all the top 20 companies had lodged their
statements with the ASX.
</P>
<P>
Those that fail to do so will be in breach of listing rule 3.1
and be named to help investors make more informed investment
decisions, an ASX spokeswoman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The total compliance cost for Australia's public companies is
yet to be finalized but estimates range from 900 million U.S.
dollars to 1.8 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Australia's telecommunications giant Telstra said Monday it
would spend up to 300 million U.S. dollars to address the problem.
</P>
<P>
Among Australia's major banks, the National Australia Bank said
it would spend 153 million U.S. dollars, Australia and New Zealand
Banking Group Ltd. said it would invest 109 million U.S. dollars,
and the Commonwealth Bank of Australia said it would spend 69
million U.S. dollars in solving the problem.
</P>
<P>
Westpac bank, St. George bank, and Colonial State Bank would
also pump 24 million to 36 million U.S. dollars to fix the
problem.
</P>
<P>
Insurance giant AMP Ltd. Tuesday said it would spend around 81
million U.S. dollars on upgrading its computer systems.
</P>
<P>
Australia's biggest airline Qantas has been hit hard and is
spending 88 million U.S. dollars to ensure all systems in check.
</P>
<P>
The problems of Year 2000 bug, also known as the millennium
bug, have evolved as most computer software use only two digits to
specify a year. This means that the year 2000 would appear as 00
and would be read by a computer as 1900, potentially causing
errors on computer systems with disastrous consequences
particularly to banks and financial markets, if it is not solved
before January 1, 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
