<HEADLINE> FIFA to Consider Increase Asian Berths in 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The international soccer governing body
FIFA will consider increasing the number of Asian qualifiers in the
2002 World Cup finals to be co-hosted by Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
FIFA Director of Communication Keith Cooper said on Tuesday with
Japan and South Korea qualifying for the 2002 finals automatically,
the remaining 1.5 berths would appear too few for Asia.
</P>
<P>
FIFA will begin to discuss the issue later this year, Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
Asia presently has 3.5 berths. The one-half of a berth refers to a
slot for which the third placer in Asian qualifying round has to vie
against the Oceanian winner.
</P>
<P>
He said as it was highly unlikely that FIFA would further inflate
the present 32-team format, the additional Asian berths will mean a
cut in another federation.
</P>
<P>
Cooper praised the eco-onsciousness of Japan and South Korean fans
at these World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
He said supporters from the two countries, who have already
eliminated, brought colorful plastic bags into stadium to wave in
their group games.
</P>
<P>
After the matches the fans packed their gabbages in the bags.
</P>
</TEXT>
