<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Strives to Fight Against HIV/AIDS: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Government departments at all
levels in China have made great efforts in the prevention and
control of HIV/AIDS in the past decade, said vice health minister
Yin Dakui here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Laws, regulations and guidelines on the prevention and control
of HIV/AIDS have been drawn up based on preliminary data on the
trends of the epidemic through the establishment of surveillance
systems, Yin told the 12th World AIDS Conference being held in
Geneva.
</P>
<P>
From the identification of the first case of HIV infection in
China in 1985 to the end of March 1998, a cumulative total of more
than 10 million people underwent testing for HIV antibodies, 9,970
cases of HIV infection were reported in individuals in 30
provinces, autonomous regions or municipalities, according to Yin.
</P>
<P>
He said that there had been 290 cases of AIDS, and 173 deaths
in China. HIV infections in ethnic minorities account for 36.3
percent of the total cumulative reported infections for the
country.
</P>
<P>
Intravenous drug users account for 66.9 percent of all those
infected with HIV, Yin said. The proportion attributable to sexual
transmission is rising annually.
</P>
<P>
To fight against HIV/AIDS, expert advisory groups, associations
and foundations have been set up, and scientific research projects
have been conducted to investigate the epidemiology of HIV/AIDS,
strategies for prevention and control, vaccines, and traditional
Chinese medicine therapies.
</P>
<P>
China has established cooperative relationships with
international organizations like the Joint United Nations Program
on HIV/AIDS, The U.N. Development Program, the U.N. Children's
Fund, the World Health Organization, the World Bank, the U.N. Fund
for Population Activities, the U.N. Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization, the European Union.  
</P>
