<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, U.S. Veteran Pilots Meet Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Foes can turn into friends over
time. This is true in today's founding of the Han Decai-Edward
Foundation named after two old-time enemies, one veteran Chinese
pilot, the other American.
</P>
<P>
The 73-year-old Edward Harold and 64-year-old Han Decai were
both here at the founding ceremony. From now on, they will work
together as friends to push forward economic and cultural
exchanges between their motherlands.
</P>
<P>
"We used to be enemies, but now we are friends, and we will be
close friends in the future," said Han. "We both are old. It is
our common aspiration to do more in the interest of the Chinese
and American people in the rest of our life."
</P>
<P>
Forty five years ago, Harold, an ace pilot with 13 years of air
experience, intruded into China's territorial air space in the
northeast. His fighter plane was shot down by 19-year-old Han
Decai.
</P>
<P>
During his captivation after he bailed out of the plane and
landed in Chinese territory by parachute, Harold failed to meet
with Han in spite of his request out of curiosity.
</P>
<P>
Their first meeting came last year in Shanghai thanks to the
arrangement by the Beijing Aviation Association and an American
ace pilot association of which Harold is a member. Han had already
retired from his position as deputy commander of the Air Force of
the Nanjing Military Area Command.
</P>
<P>
They promised to meet again when U.S. President Bill Clinton is
in China.
</P>
<P>
Han explained the reason why they chose the occasion of
Clinton's China visit to mark the ceremony by saying the
significance lies in the fact that both the Chinese and U.S.
governments and people are working to promote peace and mutual
understanding.
</P>
<P>
War is temporary, but peace and friendship are everlasting,
said Harold, who arrived in Nanjing on June 26.
</P>
<P>
"Understanding between deadly enemies like us can bring them
together, and make them friends. Therefore, I believe for the
Chinese and American people in general, understanding can all the
more make them friends," Han said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
