<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: European Central Bank (ECB) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 30 (Xinhua) -- With six months to go to the formal
launch of the single European currency, the euro, European Union
countries held a ceremony Tuesday in the German financial center
of Frankfurt to celebrate the founding of the monetary watchdog
for the euro -- the European Central Bank (ECB).
</P>
<P>
From January 1999, the Frankfurt-based ECB will take over the
power from national central banks of 11 EU countries
participating in the euro to set the common monetary policies and
common interest rates for the whole euro area.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting the fact that the euro will become the currency for
not one nation but a group of them, the single European currency
will be run by a federal monetary system called the European
System of Central Banks. It will consist of the ECB and 11
national central banks of the euro member states.
</P>
<P>
Daily operations of the ECB will be managed by a six-member
executive board comprising the bank's president, Wim Duisenberg,
and five other board members: Christian Noyer of France, Eugenio
Domingo Solans of Spain, Sirkka Haemaelaeinen of Finland, Otmar
Issing of Germany and Tommaso Padoa-Schioppa of Italy.
</P>
<P>
But the supreme decision-making body of the ECB will be its
governing council which groups the bank's six executive board
members with central bank governors of the 11 euro member states.
Each of the 17 council members will have an equal vote in ECB's
decision-making.
</P>
<P>
The executive board and the 11 national central banks will be
responsible for implementing monetary policies decided by the
governing council.
</P>
<P>
In order to set up its own organization and ensure a smooth
transition from the current national monetary policies to the
future single monetary policy, the ECB actually began to be
functional on June 1 with its first executive board meeting
convening June 2, and the first governing council meeting on June
9.
</P>
<P>
The ECB governing council has decided to meet on the first
Tuesday of every month in the future. Key issues such as the
minimum reserves of the bank, and which monetary instruments would
be used, will be decided in the following months.
</P>
<P>
The council has also decided that the ECB will have four
billion euro in startup capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
