<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Container Transport Ports Sprout Along Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Since 1981, 17 ports have been
built on the Yangtze River to handle international container
transport business.
</P>
<P>
Zhangjianggang, a port in east China's Jiangsu Province, was
the earliest port for international container transport on the
Yangtze. Afterwards, such ports have been built in Jiangyin,
Nantong, Nanjing, Tongling, Wuhan, Yichang, Chongqing and other
cities.
</P>
<P>
These ports handled 433,000 TEUs (twenty-foot equivalent units)
of containers in 1997, 6.7 times the 1989 figure, according to
recent statistics from the Ministry of Communications.
</P>
<P>
About 84 percent of the handling capacity was contributed by
the ports of Nanjing, Nantong and Zhangjianggang.
</P>
<P>
Transport experts said more special berths for container
transport purposes should be built at the ports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
