<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Better-than-expected trade data
and a stronger Japanese yen helped the Australian dollar fight
back Tuesday, with the currency rallying three quarters of a U.S.
cent into the close of the financial year of 1997-1998.
</P>
<P>
Domestic statistics revealing a better-than-expected trade
deficit and an increase in Australia's exports to Asia were one
reason for the local currency's surge Tuesday, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Adding to the buoyant mood was a stronger Japanese yen against
the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
At the close of the local session in Sydney, the Australian
dollar was changing hands at 61.47 U.S. cents, significantly
higher than 60.68 U.S. cents late Monday.
</P>
<P>
Other traders attributed the rise to a firmer-than-expected
trade position in May.
</P>
<P>
While Australia's trade position continued to suffer in May,
with its balance on goods and services widening by one million
Australian dollars (614,000 U.S. dollars) to record a 315 million
U.S. dollar deficit, the seasonally adjusted figure fell within
analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
Deutsche Bank economist Richard Yetsenga said the data
indicated that Australia's exports, in level terms, to the most
troubled Asian economies appear to have bottomed.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said both exports and
imports of goods and services fell by an adjusted 1.0 percent in
May.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar also closed Tuesday 86.14 Japanese yen
from 86.02 yen and at 1.1111 German marks from 1.0990.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar began the 1997-1998 financial year 13
U.S. cents higher at 74.62 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The Asian economic crisis which has rocked the region over the
past year has been to blame for the erosion in the value of the
local currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
