<HEADLINE> More Closure May Hit S. Korean Banking Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 30 (Xinhua) -- More closures and mergers may appear
in South Korea's ailing banking system under a government program
of restructuring the the financial sector, South Korean President
Kim Dae-jung said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Those which cannot survive international competition will go
out of business,'' the president told a cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
South Korea on Monday kickstarted the effort at financial
reform by shutting down five non-viable banks whose assets and key
operations would be absorbed by five other big banks.
</P>
<P>
The announcement followed the designation earlier this month of
55 non-financial companies which were denied further bank credit
and allowed to go out of business.
</P>
<P>
The president refuted allegations that political considerations
and other motives influenced his government's selction of the five
non-viable banks.
</P>
<P>
He said: "The government observed laws and handled the case
fairly".
</P>
<P>
The listing of banks and companies as non-viable is at the core
of corporate and financial restructuring mandated under the nearly
60 billion U.S. dollars bailout by the International Monetary Fund
(IMF).
</P>
<P>
The IMF deal came after South Korea, which once enjoyed a
dynamic economic growth, plunged into economic stagnation late
last year due to massive corporate failures and bad loans by
financial institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
