<HEADLINE> Arafat Urges International Pressure on Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
Tuesday urged the international community to pressure Israel to
commit itself to its obligations of peace, the Voice of Palestine
(VOP) reported.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters after his talks with visiting Spanish
Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar, Arafat, President of the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA), blamed Israel for causing
the stalemate in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks have been stalled since March last year when
Israelis started the construction of Jewish settlement in
traditionally Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"Spain and the European union (EU) played an important role in
recovering the peace process and the international community must
put more pressure on Israel to move the process forward," Arafat
said.
</P>
<P>
Besides efforts made by Spain in the peace process, Arafat
also thanked Spain for its economic assistance to the PNA.
</P>
<P>
On his part, the Spanish guest said that the coming few weeks
will be decisive for the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the coming weeks are important," Aznar said, adding
that "the Mideast peace negotiators are running out of time."
</P>
<P>
He said the peace process is going through a difficult time,
urging the parties concerned to continue to have the will to go
forward.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two leaders exchanged views on the
current developments of the process, EU's role in reviving the
deadlocked peace process and the economic cooperation between the
two sides.
</P>
<P>
Aznar arrived in Gaza Tuesday morning for a one-day visit
after spending two days in Israel, during which he held talks
with his Israeli counterpart Benjamin Netanyahu mainly on the
peace process issue.
</P>
<P>
This was Aznar's second visit to Gaza and the previous visit
was three years ago when he was the opposition leader in Spain.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, Spain hosted a Middle East conference that opened the
door to Israel's peace talks with the Palestinians. 
</P>
