<HEADLINE> Estrada Sets Priorities for New Philippine Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- New Philippine President Joseph
Estrada Tuesday set forth a series of priority areas and a code of
conduct for his new cabinet soon after he was worn in as the
country's 13th head of state.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, 61, was sworn in at noon as president to replace Fidel
Ramos. Under the Philippine Constitution, Estrada will serve a
single six-year term.
</P>
<P>
At the first cabinet meeting in the presidential palace here,
Estrada asked his cabinet to review the remaining budget for 1998
and identify areas for further savings.
</P>
<P>
He urged the cabinet members to identify action steps to
institute reforms in the bureaucracy, including down-sizing,
anti-graft and anti-corruption measures, and improvement of
delivery of services.
</P>
<P>
The new president also asked the new cabinet members to
identify proposed reform legislation for their respective sectors
or departments, which he said should be consistent with the
framework of governance of his administration.
</P>
<P>
Announcing a 10-point Code of Conduct for cabinet members at
the meeting, Estrada urged his cabinet to "work together as a team
in the task of nation-building."
</P>
<P>
"Abuse of power and influence peddling especially by my
relatives and friends will not be tolerated in the Estrada
Administration. Institute immediate measures to eliminate
opportunities for graft and corruption. Weed out the corruption
and the incompetent," he said, explaining one of the 10 points.
</P>
<P>
Estrada also urged the cabinet members to "immediately resolve
the problems and issues affecting your areas of concern, including
those raised in the media, to avoid causing great injury or burden
to our people and the country."
</P>
<P>
Of the 22 cabinet members, four were retained from the Ramos
administration. They are Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon, Public
Works and Highways Secretary Gregorio Vigilar, Science and
Technology Secretary William Padolina, and former executive
secretary Alexander Aguirre, who was appointed as director general
of the National Security Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
