<HEADLINE> Wax Figures Donated to Hong Kong Museum of History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A set of wax figures depicting
late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping and former British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher were donated to the Hong Kong Museum of
History here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The set of two wax figures, named "The Historic Moment," were
produced by Pang Liming and Ai Desheng, artists of China's Tianjin
Academy of Fine Arts, to commemorate the first anniversary of Hong
Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
The wax figures were donated to the Hong Kong museum by two
Tianjin-based Chinese companies.
</P>
<P>
At his meeting with Thatcher, the then British prime minister,
in Beijing in September 1982, Deng stated that China was to resume
the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong in 1997 by implementing
the concept of "one country, two systems." The historic meeting
served as the prelude to the two-year-long Sino-British diplomatic
negotiations, which led to the signing of the Sino-British Joint
Declaration in 1984 on the question of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The wax figures, together with two sculptures, gifts presented
by two Chinese provinces to the Hong Kong Special Administration
Region (SAR) government last July, are to be on display in the
museum for two months starting on July 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
