<HEADLINE> China Welcomes Foreign Engagement in Postal Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- China will strengthen cooperation
with foreign business circles in its postal service and use
foreign capital, equipment and technology to develop the sector, a
spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman for the Directorate General of Posts, Postal and
Telecommunications said at a news conference that the 22nd
Congress of the Universal Postal Union (UPU) planned in Beijing
next year will provide opportunities for China to upgrade its
postal technology with foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
China will hold an international postal technology and
equipment exhibition during the conference. The exhibition will
demonstrate China's achievements in the sector in the past 50
years, the spokesman said, and help foreign business people learn
about the Chinese market and regulations.
</P>
<P>
Posts and telecommunications are key industries slated to be
developed rapidly in China in the 21st century. The postal sector
last year had an income of 27.4 billion yuan (3 billion
U.S. dollars) in business volume, an increase of 53 percent over
1996.
</P>
<P>
China is constructing a computer network to provide
comprehensive postal services nationwide, opening more postal
routes and establishing new auto-disposal mail centers. These
areas should be attractive to foreign investors, according to the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The UPU is a special institute of the United Nations, whose
22nd congress will be held in Beijing Aug. 23-Sept. 15 of next
year, with 2,000 delegates expected to attend from 189 countries
and international organizations.
</P>
<P>
Chinese president Jiang Zemin is the honorary chairman of the
organizing committee of the congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
