<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Royal Summer Resort Becomes Attraction for All (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"In the half century after the founding of the People's
Republic of China, Beidaihe has gradually changed from a special
summer resort for the royal family into a paradise for all
citizens," said Meng Fanxiang, head of the Beidaihe District.
</P>
<P>
Beidaihe, whose permanent urban population is less than 30,000
was frequented by 2.8 million people last year. The historic
record for visitors to Beidaihe was 5 million.
</P>
<P>
Even with so many visitors, the official said, there are few
complaints of overcrowding. "The coastline around Beidaihe is 260
km long;, we have enough places for every visitor," he said.
</P>
<P>
Experts on scenery and tourism often highlight advantages in
the scenic resort. It is only several hours drive from the Chinese
capital of Beijing with wide and comfortable beaches, pleasant
weather, green hills, flowing rivers and forests.
</P>
<P>
In the Beidaihe area, you can see the starting point of the
Great Wall -- Shanhaiguan -- and Laolongtou, a unique section of
the Great Wall which was built into the sea.
</P>
<P>
Now, Beidaihe and Laolongtou are both listed among the 40 best
tourist attractions in China.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, bird-watching is becoming increasingly popular in
Beidaihe, with a foliage coverage of 44 percent. Through
telescopes people watch birds over the sea waves, on beaches and
spotted in the dense woods.
</P>
<P>
"I and my group have seen some 300 species of birds here in the
past few days; it is really one of the best places to watch birds
and enjoy the beauty of nature," said a British ornithologist who
has been to Beidaihe six times.
</P>
<P>
Another bird-watching lover, Dr. T.Martin from the Cambridge
University, wrote a book on his experience and studies in
Beidaihe, which led to the opening of an international seminar on
water bird conservation in Beidaihe. Experts and officials
attending the seminar had even worked out a "Beidaihe Declaration"
to protect birds and their habitats.
</P>
<P>
To mark the 100th anniversary of the Beidaihe summer resort,
the Beidaihe local government recently decided to build an even
better home for birds -- hundreds of birds of varying species will
live in a newly planted forest.
</P>
<P>
"We hope our efforts can not only add beauty to nature, but
help raise the natural conversational awareness among visitors,"
Liu Hongbin, a local official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Royal Summer Resort Becomes Attraction for All (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Asking for directions can be a
big problem in Beidaihe, a famous summer resort in China's north
coast. In winter, there are very few people in the streets; and in
summer nine-tenths of the passers-by are tourists.
</P>
<P>
This year signifies the centennial of Beidaihe summer resort,
which is located in Qinhuangdao City of Hebei Province. Most train
tickets to the small town are booked even before the hot weather
arrives.
</P>
<P>
One government employee Zhang Huiqin in Beijing said that as
early as April, a long list of names wishing to spend their
one-week summer vacation in Beidaihe has been decided in his
work unit.
</P>
<P>
"I come here almost every year; it is beautiful, clean and not
polluted," she said.
</P>
<P>
Though most holiday-goers come to escape the summer heat and
enjoy the beaches, and some come to view unique natural landscape,
such as a couple from east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
"I feel the name of Beidaihe means so much beauty and
attraction, with a kind of mystery," said Wang Cunzhao, the
husband.
</P>
<P>
"I knew when I was a child that Beidaihe is a resort where
high-ranking government officials used to have meetings during the
summertime, but only very recently did I know that it also opened
to common people long ago," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he and his wife had decided to come and stay longer
next year.
</P>
<P>
According to historical documents, the first villa in Beidaihe
appeared in 1893, and most visitors then were foreign business
people.
</P>
<P>
In 1898, the imperial court of late Qing dynasty (1644-1911)
then decided formerly to turn Beidahe into a summer resort.
</P>
</TEXT>
