<HEADLINE> Seoul Stocks Down Amid Worry About Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Seoul stock prices edged down 0.24
percent Tuesday because of concern over reform of the banking
sector.
</P>
<P>
The composite stock price index dropped 0.72 points to close
the day at 297.88. Losers outnumbered gainers at 497 to 286, with
101 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Trading was light with 52.5 million shares worth 248.2 billion
won (about 177.2 million U.S. dollars) changing hands, compared
with the Monday's 65.4 million issues.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the South Korean government began its restructuring
of financial institutions by ordering five non-viable banks to be
merged by five well-managed banks.
</P>
<P>
Investment sentiment was depressed as backlash erupted from
employees of the five ailing banks Daedong, Dongnam, Dongwha,
Kyungki and Chungchong, protesting the government's decision.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of the closure of five weak banks announced
will make good banks weak and worsen their asset quality, said Lee
Yong, manager of Daewoo Securities Co. "Thus, I think, the
government failed to ease anxieties among foreign investors over
their holdings of financial issues.''
</P>
<P>
Due to growing concerns over the financial restructuring,
shares of most banks, brokerage houses, and insurance firms
retreated substantially, stock dealers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
