<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Head of the Egyptian-Moroccan Businessmen Council
Yamani Felfilah said they plan to set up the first share holding
Arab navigation company serving North Africa Arab countries, the
Arab daily Alalam Alyoum reported here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The main business of the planned company, with an investment of
100 million U.S. dollars, will be for passenger and cargo
transport.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem -- israel's prospective purchase of Egyptian gas
could push bilateral trade into the multi-billion-dollar range,
Israel-Egypt Chamber of Industry and Commerce President Albert
Papouchado said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Presently their trade volume stands at 100 million U.S. dollars
each year. Negotiation between Israel and Egypt for the purchase
of gas produced in the Sinai peninsula broke down more than a year
ago, leading Israel to consider importing liquefied natural gas
from Nigeria, Norway, Australia or constructing a pipeline from
regions of the former Soviet Union or Qatar.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Foreign ministers from the nine Arab countries along
the southern Mediterranean basin will meet in Cairo on July 22 to
discuss the setup of an Arab-Mediterranean free trade zone to
facilitate the Euro-Mediterranean integration.
</P>
<P>
The Arab daily Alalam Alyoum reported Tuesday that the move
aims to further boost economic and trade cooperation and
facilitate the influx of investments.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member EU and 12 nations along the southern
Mediterranean basin, including the nine Arab states, established
Euro-Med Partnership in 1995 aimed at achieving a free trade zone
in Europe and the Mediterranean by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem -- Israel's short-term foreign debt has almost doubled
over the past two years compared to its level during the first six
years of this decade, the Bank of Israel said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The debt totaled about 8.5 billion U.S. dollars in 1997 and the
first quarter of 1998, compared to 4.3 billion dollar between 1990
and 1996, the bank said. Most of the increase was due to rising
private-sector borrowing, currently accounting for some 80 percent
of the total short-term foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Secretary General of the Egyptian Chamber of Commerce,
Mohammed Al-Masry, said that they are planning to build a bridge
across the Aqaba Gulf to link Egypt and Saudi Arabia, the Arab
daily Alalam Alyoum reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
With the new bridge, the travelers will not need to transit in
Jordan, Al-Masry said.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The trade volume between Egypt and the U.S. in the
first four months this year has reached 1.2 billion dollars, the
Egyptian daily Alalam Alyoum reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Trade and Supply, Ahmed Gowaili, said Egypt exports
to the U.S. amounted to 226 million dollars and imports from the
country reached 965 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's unemployment rate rose to a new record
high of 8.8 percent in April. Since the beginning of this year,
the jobless rate has been rising steadily, from 8.3 percent in
January to 8.5 percent in February and 8.7 percent in March. The
annual unemployment rate in 1997 was 7.7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
