<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Inaugurates Childen's Hospital in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton, wife of
visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton, inaugurated a medical center
for children in the Pudong New Area of Shanghai today.
</P>
<P>
"Certainly the relationship between our two countries and our
two peoples has no more important objective than improving the
future for children of both our countries," Hillary said after
cutting ribbons for a U.S.-China joint venture medical center.
</P>
<P>
The inauguration ceremony is a separate program that the U.S.
first lady participated from those of President Clinton during
their first full-day stay in Shanghai, the third leg of their
9-day and 5-city visit to China.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Children's Medical Center is a cooperative project
between the Shanghai No. 2 University of Medical Sciences and
Project HOPE of the United States. It is the most comprehensive
and best equipped children's hospital in China.
</P>
<P>
Hillary said that the hospital is a successful example of
friendship and cooperation between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
"China's children are as beautiful, bright, intelligent as
those I saw in Xi'an, Beijing and Shanghai. I believe China will
surely have a bright future," she said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-China friendship and cooperation in the field of
medical and health care constitute an important part of friendly
cooperation between the two countries, she said.
</P>
<P>
After inaugurating the children's hospital, Hillary went to
Shanghai Women's Training Center to learn about training of
women for re-employment in the city. She attended classes of
tailoring and flower arrangement at the training center.
</P>
<P>
The training center has offered training courses for 3,000 laid
off female workers.
</P>
<P>
Hillary, a graduate of Wellesley College of the U.S., also paid
a visit to the only girls' school in Shanghai. She talked with
students at the No. 3 Girls' School and answered their questions.
</P>
<P>
She said that she is impressed with Shanghai because it is
"dynamic, growing and oriented to the future."  
</P>
