<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Thickest Loess Layer In China's Yellow River Valley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The world's thickest loess layer
is not, as scientists might have expected, on a mountainside, but
in fact in the valley of a local Yellow River section, a Chinese
geologist reports.
</P>
<P>
Associate Professor Hu Xiaohong, a geologist the the
Northwestern National Minorities College, said that exploration in
the village of Xijin, in the capital of China's Gansu Province,
revealed a loess layer there about 410 meters thick, the thickest
ever found.
</P>
<P>
According to Associate Prof. Hu, the layer was formed some 200
million years ago and will be useful for the study of climate
changes in the past.
</P>
<P>
Loess deposits formed under varied climate conditions have
diversified features, and the thickest loess layer is located
between the Mongolian Plateau and the Loess Plateau, he
acknowledged, saying that the Loess Plateau covers a total area of
400,000 sq.km, and the average thickness of its layer is 50-80 m.,
and so is the world's largest loess area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
