<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Should Move into Hi-Tech: Scholar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- For future economic growth and
dynamism, Hong Kong should move from a services-oriented economy
into a hi-tech center, a Taiwan scholar said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Battered by the regional financial turmoil, Hong Kong has been
experiencing a painful economic adjustment. A growing number of
people inside and outside Hong Kong are rethinking about the
nature of economic activities in Hong Kong and the need to make
necessary changes, Yung Wei, president of Vanguard Institute for
Policy Studies, Taiwan, told a two-day Hong Kong Economic Forum
ended here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Foremost among the conclusions of the soul-searching efforts
concerning the structure of Hong Kong economy is that Hong Kong
must move from a service-oriented economy to that of hi-tech,"
Wei noted, who is also a professor of science at a Taiwan
university.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, Hong Kong had a manufacturing industry which
constituted 21.9 percent of the total economy. Since then there
has been a steady decline of the industrial sector of Hong Kong
economy owing to the relocation of labor-intensive industries to
neighboring Pearl River Delta region.
</P>
<P>
By 1994, the manufacture sector of Hong Kong economy dwindled
to 7.2 percent. As a result, service sector has become the major
part of Hong Kong economy.
</P>
<P>
"With the upsurge of the Asian financial crisis, the
vulnerability of Hong Kong service-oriented economy has become
increasingly evident," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
A new avenue for future economic growth and dynamism "lies in
high technology, meaning information science and industry,
communication technology and bio-technology, to name just a few,"
he noted.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that Hong Kong, a late comer in hi-tech
development, attract talent from both China's mainland and abroad.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Economic Forum, under the theme of "Free Market
Economy -- the Way Forward," was held just prior to the first
anniversary of Hong Kong's return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the forum were over 40 senior officials, think-tank
members and business leaders from Hong Kong and overseas,
according to Paul Yip, chairman of the Hong Kong Policy Research
Institute, which organized the forum together with the Hong Kong
Trade Development Council.
</P>
<P>
Topics covered Hong Kong as an international trade and
financial center, information and communications, human capital
development, the future of Hong Kong's industry, Asian values and
global partnership, the Asian economic crisis and the world
economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace, Good Governance Prerequisites for COMESA's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA)'s efforts will bear no fruits without
peace, political stability and democratic governance, Zambian
President Frederick Chiluba has said.
</P>
<P>
In his keynote address Monday at the start of COMESA's third
summit in Kinshasa, capital of the Democratic Republic of Congo,
Chiluba said civil strikes and the simmering political conflicts
between some of the COMESA member states were a cause of great
concern.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, the COMESA's Chairman, said that most of the
conflicts within and between states were due to factors which can
be resolved through discussion and have hampered the
organization's efforts to achieve sustainable economic
development and regional integration, the Malawi News Agency
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever their nature, the answer to them will not be found
in military confrontation. Guns will have the effect of
exacerbating the problems. Let us desist from war," said Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Presidents of Zambia, Zimbabwe, Namibia, Burundi, Malawi,
Kenya and the Democratic Republic of Congo, attended the one-day
summit whose theme is "information as a tool for increased trade
and investment in the COMESA."
</P>
<P>
COMESA exists to assist member states in achieving economic
recovery and sustainable growth and development.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian president called on COMESA to speed up and deepen
social and economic ties between its member states to address the
causes of conflicts.
</P>
<P>
To deny people the political right to choose their own system
of government is undemocratic and as such, a condition which is a
recipe for political and social tension and conflicts, he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that democratic government was vital for economic
development and regional integration.
</P>
<P>
On the theme of the summit, Chiluba said the successful
economies in the 21st century will be those that keep on adapting
to the continuous changes in technological systems.
</P>
<P>
"The investment and trade opportunities that abound in COMESA
can only be rationally and fully exploited through the
development of land based and satellite communications systems,"
Chiluba said.
</P>
<P>
Laurent Kabila, President of the Democratic Republic of Congo
called on countries in Africa to reject what he said are attempts
by some elements to paint a bad picture of his country.
</P>
<P>
He urged COMESA countries to join hands with his nation,
saying his country is willing to place its vast natural resources
at the disposal of Africa and the COMESA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
