<HEADLINE> FM Spokesman on India's Response to Sino-U.S. Joint Statement on South Asia Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- It is the common wish for the
international community to require both India and Pakistan to put
an end to the nuclear arms race and ease the tension in the region.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman Tang Guoqiang made this
remark at a regular news conference here this afternoon. "We have
taken note of the different responses from India and Pakistan to
the Sino-U.S. joint statement on the South Asia situation signed
during U.S. President Clinton's China trip," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan reportedly expressed its welcome to the joint
statement, whereas India also voiced its own views on it, Tang
said.
</P>
<P>
Tang went on say that the joint Sino-U.S. statement was another
statement on the South Asia issue after one reached earlier during
the Geneva meeting by the foreign ministers of the Five Permanent
Members of the the United Nations Security Council .
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Tang quoted the Sino-U.S. statement as saying that
"both China and the United States concern themselves with nuclear
tests by the two countries and the ensuing escalation of tension
that arises therefrom."
</P>
<P>
Also, both the Chinese and U.S. sides share common interests in
safeguarding peace and stability in the South Asia region and in
the powerful mechanism for global non-proliferation, Tang said,
They are resolved to increase their efforts for nuclear
non-proliferation, so as to help promote India-Pakistan
reconciliation and proceed to resolve the differences between
India and Pakistan through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
This conforms to the common aspiration of the international
community to oppose nuclear proliferation," Tang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
