<HEADLINE> Clinton Discusses Soccer World Cup With Shanghai Fans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. President Bill
Clinton today discussed about the ongoing World Cup soccer
tournament with local fans, saying that the defending champion --
Brazil is the most possible winner.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question about who he thinks will win the
soccer World Cup this time, President Clinton, who was attending a
live talk show at Radio Shanghai, said: "It's hard for me to
predict. I'm not an expert on soccer, but the Brazilians are
always hard to beat."
</P>
<P>
"I've watched them play a lot, and they're always very good,"
the president added. Brazil has won the Cup for four times, more
than any other nations worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the U.S. national soccer team which lost to
the Iranians 1-2, leading to the elimination of the U.S. team from
the Cup, Clinton said the defeat was "heartbreaking for
Americans".
</P>
<P>
However, he conceded that the Iranians "beat us fair and
square".
</P>
<P>
"The Iranians had two fast breaks and they played with such
passion when they had those two chances that they capitalized on
both of them and we respect that," said the president, who
obviously watched this game.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed hope that this World Cup clash of soccer
teams would help improve the long-lasting tense relations between
the U.S. and Iran.
</P>
<P>
"It could be possible," he said when asked if this "football
diplomacy" could work.
</P>
<P>
"I think the World Cup is a great way of bringing people
together," he said.
</P>
<P>
At a round-table discussion with local residents at the
Shanghai Library earlier today, Clinton said that he would be glad
to have a teaching post in the prestigious Fudan University.
</P>
<P>
Claiming that he has made no final plans for the years after
the end of his presidential term in two and a half years, Clinton
said that maybe he would apply for a visiting professorship in
Fudan.
</P>
<P>
Xie Xide, physicist and former president of Fudan, told the
U.S. president that he is more than welcome to be a visiting
professor in the university only on one condition, if he can speak
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
To which Clinton merrily answered, "I am not too old to learn."
</P>
</TEXT>
