<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti, Pakistani Leaders Talks on Nuclear Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti and Pakistani leaders
opened talks here Tuesday on a wide-range of issues, especially
nuclear tension in South Asia, Kuwaiti official news agency Kuna
reported.
</P>
<P>
The talks was co-chaired by Kuwaiti Crown Prince and Prime
Minister Sheikh Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Salem Al-Sabah and visiting
Pakistani Prime Minister Mohammad Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Kuna did not give details about of the talks, but local
newspapers reported earlier that they would focus on nuclear
tensions in South Asia, as well as ways of boosting bilateral
relations and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Sharif, who arrived here Monday on a two-day official visit,
also met with Kuwaiti Emir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait sent a special envoy last month to Islamabad to express
solidarity with the Pakistani people after India conducted five
nuclear tests on May 11 and 13.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, in response to the Indian tests, exploded six of its
own devices, which prompted foreign sanctions. Sharif then
launched a national self-reliance fund to fight the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month Sharif visited the United Arab Emirates
(UAE) and Saudi Arabia, and urged hundreds of thousands of
overseas Pakistanis to contribute to the fund.
</P>
<P>
Sharif is scheduled to meet Pakistani expatriates working in
Kuwait at a public meeting. 
</P>
