<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Vows to Fight Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada, in his inaugural speech, on Tuesday reiterated that his
government will give priority to poverty alleviation, food
security for the poor, and the restoration of peace and order in
the country.
</P>
<P>
"We will educate their children and foster their health. We
will bring peace and security, jobs and dignity to the law," said
Estrada at a grand rally in down Manila.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, who was sworn in at noon Tuesday, also promised to
provide "a roof over the heads of the poor, food on their tables
and clothes on their backs."
</P>
<P>
Estrada, who won the May 11 presidential polls on a populist
pro-poor platform, said the era of the Filipino masses has arrived
with his election as president.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, who had been vice president since 1992, has vowed to
cut the country's current 34 percent poverty incidence to 20
percent within his six-year term.
</P>
<P>
"It is time to speed up the improvement of the living
conditions of the common people, time for them to have a fairer
share of the national wealth they create and a bigger stake in
their own country," Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, a former action movie star famous for playing Robin
Hood-style heroes fighting for the poor, also vowed to crack down
on rampant criminal syndicates in the country.
</P>
<P>
Estrada took time to laud former President Fidel Ramos for
laying the foundation of a strong economy, which has sustained
significant growth for years.
</P>
<P>
The new president admitted that his immediate challenge will be
the currency crisis-battered economy. But he did not elevate his
economic policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
