<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poverty Alleviation Priority in Malawian Economy: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Malawian government has noted
that poverty alleviation remains the center-piece of its economic
program.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Cassim Chilumpha made the remarks when he
presented the country's 1998/99 budget in parliament in Malawi's
capital Lilongwe, the Malawi News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He presented a 631.3-million-US-Dollar budget for the 1998/99
financial year, of which 381 million Dollars has been earmarked
for recurrent expenditure and 251 million Dollars for development
expenditure.
</P>
<P>
Of the 251-million-Dollar development expenditure, Chilumpha
said, only 25 million Dollars will come from local resources
while 216 million Dollars will be funded from foreign loans and
grants.
</P>
<P>
"Government has made deliberate allocations in favor of
priority sectors like education, health, agriculture, works,
water development and forestry," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If these important areas are improved, we believe poverty
among our people now will be eradicated," Chilumpha added.
</P>
<P>
The minister said government has placed "special emphasis" on
effective expenditure control and prudent financial management to
avoid unnecessary over-expenditure.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the government overspent by 24 million Dollars
has raised some eyebrows within international lending
institutions like the International Monetary Fund and the World
Bank as to how the over expenditure came about when a "cash
budget system" was in place.
</P>
<P>
But Chilumpha contended that some unforeseen natural
occurrences compounded by some fiscal indiscipline among
controlling officers contributed to the over-expenditure.
</P>
<P>
"This year's budget will therefore, aim at consolidating
structural reforms and expenditure priorities vital for
socio-economic progress.
</P>
<P>
"In 1997/98 fiscal year, there was a 10 percent overall budget
deficit" because of "financing pressure on budget, due to imports
of maize and relief operations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Inflation rose from one percent in 1996 to 20.2 percent in
1997. But Chilumpha was optimistic that with sound economic
measures now in place inflation rate will drop to 10 percent by
December this year.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the country expects agriculture output to
grow by 4.7 percent in 1998 with small scale farming contributing
a leading 6.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Maize production is expected to increase by 25 percent to 1.76
million metric tons and manufacturing by 7.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
He expressed concern that tobacco exports, the country's
largest foreign exchange earner, will continue showing signs of
decline with average prices falling to 29 percent in the current
trend.
</P>
<P>
The minister also announced customs and excise measures to
enhance trade liberalization and stimulate production which
include: reduction in maximum duty rates from 40 percent to 30
percent, and industrial machines' rates from 15 percent to 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
Also included are designated raw materials and intermediate
goods which will be reduced from 15 percent to 10 percent, and 10
to 5 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
According to Chilumpha, "overall budget reflects government's
determination to improve the lives of people and also propel the
Malawian economy into the next millennium with rapid growth and
rising social welfare." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
