<HEADLINE> Fiji Soldiers Guard Hydro Power Plant Against Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A company of soldiers from the
Fiji Military Forces Tuesday would take over security operations
at the country's main hydro power station with orders to shoot
trespassers, the Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
The Monasavu Hydroelectric installation in the mountains of
Viti Levu, the country's main island, was the target of an arson
attack over the weekend that caused Fiji Prime Minister Sitiveni
Rabuka to cut short a visit to Australia to deal with the crisis,
the AAP reported from Suva, capital of Fiji.
</P>
<P>
Fiji Minister for Home Affairs Colonel Paul Manueli said
Tuesday that the soldiers had been told to use firearms if needed,
the wire service said.
</P>
<P>
Trouble started brewing in the area around the installation
over the weekend as an office block was destroyed by fire on
Sunday after the government ignored a demand by landowners last
week for 35 million Fiji dollars (17 million U.S. dollars) in
compensation for their land.
</P>
<P>
Investigations are continuing into the blaze and no arrests
have been made, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Col. Manueli, a former commander of the Fiji army, said more
than 100 soldiers would take over the security of the
hydroelectric installation from police later Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
He said there had been about 100 policemen deployed over the
past week in the area, 80 kilometers northwest of Suva.
</P>
<P>
He added that the soldiers would remain in the area as long as
they were required.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a special cabinet sub-committee has been appointed
to look into the landowners' demands and make recommendations next
month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
