<HEADLINE> President Jiang Zemin Arrives in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
arrived here by special plane Tuesday afternoon to attend the
celebrations of the first anniversary of the establishment of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who is also general secretary of the Central Committee
of the Communist Party of China (CPC) and chairman of the Central
Military Commission, and his wife Wang Yeping flew into Hong Kong
from Beijing in the company of SAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
and his wife Betty Tung.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's entourage, including Vice-Premier Qian Qichen and his
wife, Alternate Member of the Political Bureau of the CPC Central
Committee Zeng Qinghong, Member of the Central Military Commission
and Chief of General Staff of the Chinese People's Liberation Army
Fu Quanyou, Director of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office of
the State Council Liao Hui, arrived by the same plane.
</P>
<P>
Jiang and his party were greeted at the Kai Tak Airport by
Andrew Li Kwok-nang, chief justice of the Court of Final Appeal of
the HKSAR, the SAR's Administrative Secretary Anson Chan,
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang, Secretary for Justice Elsie
Leung, Convenor of the Executive Council Chung Sze-yuen, and
Provisional Legislative Council President Rita Fan.
</P>
<P>
Among those present at the airport to greet President Jiang
were also Jiang Enzhu, director of the Xinhua News Agency Hong
Kong Branch, Ma Yuzhen, commissioner of the Chinese Foreign
Ministry in HKSAR, and Liu Zhenwu, commander of the People's
Liberation Army (PLA) Garrison in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Some 150 children waving China's national flags and SAR
regional flags were at the airport to greet Jiang and his party.
Jiang was presented with a bouquet of flowers amidst music played
by a police band.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Hong Kong, Jiang is scheduled to attend a
grand gathering to celebrate the anniversary on July 1, inspect
troops of the PLA stationed in Hong Kong, and officiate at the
opening of the new international airport at Chek Lap Kok on July
2.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong returned to China on July 1, 1997, when Jiang
attended a ceremony here and declared that China resumed the
exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giant Flight Kitchen To Open at New Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- One of the world's largest
flight kitchens will start operation on July 6 this year, the same
day the Hong Kong new airport at Chek Lap Kok opens for commercial
aviation.
</P>
<P>
Located on the southeast corner of Chek Lap Kok, the
three-story catering facility has a gross floor area of 50,400
square meters, ranking third in the world, according to Paul
Stuart, project manager of Cathay Pacific Catering Services
(CPCS), the company that operates the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
The new building houses a complex production line capable of
handling 80,000 flight meals per day, putting it among the top
five around the globe. But Stuart said Tuesday that the facility
would turn out some 40,000 meals per day at opening as the demand
shrank in the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
A 3.3-km-long conveyor belt within the building transports
goods and trays, similar to a car assembly line. There are also a
320-meter-long bank of washing machines and a 500-meter-long
vacuum waste system.
</P>
<P>
A computer-controlled system enables automatic dispatch and
retrieval of goods and carts, creating a high degree of
efficiency, said the project manager.
</P>
<P>
It took two years to construct the catering facility at a cost
of 1.6 billion HK dollars (200 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
CPCS, a wholly-owned subsidiary of Hong Kong's flagship
airline, Cathay Pacific Airways, now operates at Kai Tak Airport a
flight kitchen. It produces an average of 35,000 meals a day for
35 airlines, taking a 70 percent market share for airline catering
services in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
On July 5 night, CPCS will take part in the dramatic overnight
relocation of facilities from Kai Tak to Chek Lap Kok. It will
transfer 70,000 trays, 40,000 glasses, 70,000 sets of utensils,
and 2,000 meal carts in 90 six-meter-long containers, and almost
100 catering vehicles such as refrigerated trucks and
high-loaders.
</P>
<P>
"All the load will have to be in place when the new airport
opens on July 6," said Stuart. 
</P>
</TEXT>
