<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Million Afghan Refugees Return Home Since 1988: UNHCR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The four millionth Afghan refugee
has recently returned home while 2.6 million remain in exile, the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) said here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
For much of the 1980s, Afghan refugees accounted for almost
half of the world's total and, by the end of the decade, the
number of refugees peaked at 6.2 million, said the UNHCR.
</P>
<P>
Since 1988, more than 2.7 million Afghans have returned from
Pakistan and 1.3 million from Iran. There are still around 1.4
million refugees living in Iran and 1.2 million in Pakistan, with
hundreds of thousands more scattered across the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) and other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
"This staggering number of returnees is a record for any
refugee group since World War II," said UNHCR chief Sadako
Ogata. "Tragically, Afghanistan also still holds the record as
UNHCR's largest single refugee case load in the world for the 18th
year in succession, around 2.6 million at present."
</P>
<P>
Despite the achievements in refugee repatriation, UNHCR said
that it is struggling to raise funds for the continued
repatriation and reintegration of Afghan refugees.
</P>
<P>
With more than half the year gone, the agency only has 4.5
million U.S. dollars available out of its original projected 1998
budget of 21 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR officials warned that if funds continued to remain in
short supply, many refugees who would like to return might be
deterred from doing so since the agency would be unable to carry
out vital rehabilitation work in their home areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
