<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Nino Wrecks Havoc in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Floods and diseases brought
about by El Nino created widespread havoc in Tanzania, killing
416 people and affecting 2.4 million others,, an official has
said here.
</P>
<P>
The floods resulted from El Nino from last October to May this
year have also destroyed 37,615 houses and 221,945 hectares of
crops, Kingunge Ngombale-Mwiru, the Minister of State in the
Prime Minister's Office said Monday while addressing parliament,
known as the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Other effects caused by El Nino include eruption of contagious
diseases like cholera, dysentery, crop and animal diseases, as
well as breeding of rodents and green hoppers, the official was
quoted by Tuesday's newspaper The Guardian as saying.
</P>
<P>
The floods have also played havoc with roads, bridges and
railways, he said, adding that international community have
agreed to donate 35.3 billion Shillings (about 53.6 million U.S.
Dollars) to Tanzania for repairing major roads and bridges in
various parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Of the amount, the World Bank will disburse 39.9 million U.S.
Dollars as its general contribution and another 11.68 million
U.S. Dollars for emergency rehabilitation of major roads.
</P>
<P>
He told the National Assembly that Britain will also
contribute 1.3 billion Shillings (about 1.97 million U.S.
Dollars) for rehabilitation of bridges in selected roads in the
country.
</P>
<P>
So far, the government has appropriated 2.4 billion Shillings
(about 3.64 million U.S. Dollars) to the Road Fund for emergency
road repair, 63.3 million Shillings (about 96,000 U.S. Dollars)
on rehabilitation of airports and 11.8 billion Shillings (about
1.79 million U.S. Dollars) have been allocated in the 1998/99
financial year to deal with El Nino effects, Ngombale-Mwiru said.
</P>
<P>
The short-term program to rehabilitate the infrastructure as a
result of El Nino is estimated to cost 189 million U.S. Dollars
whereas long-term measures will cost 163 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last month, presidents of Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda met in
north Tanzania's Arusha, appealing to donors to assist the three
countries in building and repairing road network.
</P>
<P>
The donor community has promised to grant the three countries
more than one billion U.S. Dollars for the first phase of the
scheme. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
