<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FM Spokesman: US President Clinton's Visit A Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton's
visit to China is crowned with success, said Foreign Ministry
spokesman Tang Guoqiang at a regular news conference here today.
</P>
<P>
The visit has expanded the exchanges and cooperation between
the two sides in a wide range of fields, increased the American
people's understanding of China and the friendship between the
people of the two countries, so that new progress has been made
toward the goal of establishing Sino-U.S. constructive strategic
partnership.
</P>
<P>
During President Clinton's visit, Tang noted, President Jiang
Zemin had formal talks with him and Premier Zhu Rongji had working
luncheon in his honor, and both the talks and meetings are
positive, constructive and fruitful.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of both nations underlined that improvement and
development of Sino-US relations not only tally with the interests
of both countries, but are also conducive to the peace, stability
and development of the world as a whole at present and in the
coming 21st century, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side underlined that Taiwan question is the most
important and sensitive crucial issue in the Sino-US relations,
and the US adherence to the principles and relevant commitments
enshrined in the three communiques and proper handling of the
Taiwan issue play a key role in the healthy, stable development
of the relationship, according to Tang.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton reiterated that the United States keeps to
its one-China policy, abides by the three joint communiques signed
between the two nations, does not support Taiwan independence,
does not support "one China, one-Taiwan" or "two Chinas", and does
not support Taiwan's entry to any international organization
composed of independent states.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the two sides had an exchange of views on
international situation, situation in south Asia, and the Asian
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, both sides decide to increase their strategic
dialogues in the economic and banking fields, and adopt further
measures to promote cooperation in Sino-U.S trade, energy and
environment, science and technology, culture, education, health
care, law and military fields and people-to-people exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, both sides have agreed to expand bilateral trade on
the basis of equality and mutual benefit, and made progress in
their talks on China's entry into the World Trade Organization
(WTO), and both sides announced not to target their nuclear
weapons at each other's countries, Tang Guoqiang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
