<HEADLINE> Japan to Lift Travel Warning for Lima </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto told Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori Tuesday that
Japan is considering lifting a travel advisory warning against
Japanese tourists visiting Lima.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, in a meeting with Fujimori, said that Japan will
withdraw the warning after an evaluation of the security
conditions there is made, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The warning was posted 10 days after a group of Peruvian
leftist guerrillas stormed the Japanese ambassador's residence in
the Peruvian capital on December 17, 1996 and took hundreds
hostage.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian government has been seeking to relax the Japanese
advisory to help spur the country's tourism industry since Peru
resolved the hostage crisis by using force on April 22, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori arrived here Sunday for a four-day visit to attend an
international symposium, which was opened by Hashimoto earlier in
the day, to promote economic exchange between Japan and countries
in Latin America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto and Fujimori were joined in their meeting by
Uruguayan President Julio Maria Sanguinetti, during which the
three leaders briefly discussed the generally good health of the
Latin American economy in contrast to Japan's sluggish business
outlook, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
