<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Scales Down Revenue Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Following the economic downturn
caused by the on-going currency crisis, the Philippine government
has scaled down its total revenue target from 527 billion pesos
(13.1 billion U.S. dollars) to 488 billion pesos (12.2 billion
dollars) for this year.
</P>
<P>
In a transition report published here Tuesday, out-going
Finance Secretary Salvador Enriquez said that the revenue target
of the Bureau of Internal Revenue has been downscaled to 367
billion pesos (9.1 billion dollars) for 1998, instead of the
original projection of 378 billion pesos (9.4 billion dollars)
because of the slowdown of the economic growth in the country.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, he said, the revenue target of the Bureau of Customs
for this year has been reduced to 83.6 billion pesos (2 billion
dollars) instead of the original target of 123.6 billion pesos (3
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
To achieve the revised target, the secretary said, the new
government of President Joseph Estrada must continue with tax
reforms.
</P>
<P>
Estrada was sworn in Tuesday as the new president to replace
Fidel Ramos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
