<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Worry over Increased Drug Trade in W. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- As the world marked this year's
international day against drug trafficking and abuse at the
weekend, experts have expressed concern over the alarming
increase of drug trade in west Africa.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the African Council of Narcotics (ACON)
Tuesday attributed the major factors for the increased drug trade
in the sub-region to the "very tricky" drug traffickers,
especially Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
"They evolve newer and more sophisticated methods and
strategies to move their consignment" to consuming nations of
America and Europe, it said.
</P>
<P>
Other factors that make it easier for the drug trade to
increasingly flourish in the sub-region, noted ACON President
Deacon Bassey Rekpene, include "very porous borders, poor control
of the vast land, air and waterways of the region."
</P>
<P>
He also cited as worsening the problem "corrupt law
enforcement officers, many of whom are only too willing to look
the other way for fat tips and lack of equipment and skilled
manpower for effective movement of drugs."
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS (Economic Community of West African States) treaty,
which allows free movement of persons and goods within the
sub-region is now being abused and used for drug trafficking,
according to him.
</P>
<P>
"Nigerian or Ghanaian traffickers drop their international
passports in Abidjan or Banjul from where they move cocaine or
heroin to Liberia, Sierra Leone, Benin, Burkina Faso or Lagos
with their ECOWAS traveling certificates for onward
transshipment," he said.
</P>
<P>
West African traffickers now transship cocaine from south
America and heroin from Asia to the United States, Canada and
continue in Europe through Cape Verde, Equatorial Guinea,
Nigeria, Cote d'Ivoire, Benin, Togo and Ghana mostly.
</P>
<P>
The civil wars in Liberia, Sierra Leone and Guinea Bissau, and
political tensions among countries of the sub-region escalated
the social problem of drug abuse, he noted.
</P>
<P>
However, the ACON president blamed the problem of cultivation
and production of Indian hemp, the predominant drug of the
sub-region, on poverty.
</P>
<P>
"Majority of the countries within west Africa fall in the
category of least-developed countries with per capita income
ranging from less than 100 to 1,000 U.S. Dollars a year, with
gross domestic product of not up to 1,000 Dollars," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Official Urges Int'l Help to Address Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Help from the international
community is needed to address the current economic crisis as the
prosperity and well-being of Southeast and East Asia are very
important to the world, U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Actions of each nation affect other nations as never before,"
Rubin said during his speech at the renowned Chularlongkorn
University Tuesday noon.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, every nation has the responsibility to help address
the problems faced by other nations, he added.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that during the current economic turmoil in the
region, the World Bank, the Asian Development Bank and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) lent a hand to the affected
nations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United States and Japan jointly intervened in
the money market when the Japanese yen plummeted to a record-low
level in nearly eight years.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested nations affected by the crisis strengthen
their financial sectors, increase government transparency and let
the financial institutions shoulder greater responsibility for
their own activities.
</P>
<P>
As for Japan, Rubin said the United States is "deeply
concerned" about the weaknesses of the Japanese economy, which is
critical to the economic health of the region and the world as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed the recent fiscal stimulus policies of the Japanese
government, hailing them as the "first step forward."
</P>
<P>
When talking about China that he had just visited as a member
of President Bill Clinton's entourage, Rubin said China's success
is important to the world.
</P>
<P>
China's strong commitment to maintaining its foreign exchange
rate is "a source of stability" of the region and the world, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin arrived here on Monday as part of a four-nation tour in
Asia, which has taken him to China and Malaysia and will also take
him to South Korea.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai earlier
Tuesday, Rubin hailed the progress the government has achieved,
saying it has adopted "sound policies".
</P>
<P>
Rubin affirmed that his country supports additional IMF funding
to Thailand if needed. 
</P>
