<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise for 5th Straight Day in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed higher in Tokyo
on Tuesday for the fifth consecutive trading day as the Japanese
yen's firm resistance against the U.S. dollar encouraged both
institutional investors and speculators.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section at the Tokyo Stock Exchange jumped 464.54 points, or 3.02
percent, from Monday's close to finish at 15,830.27.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, advanced 28.16 points or 2.34 percent to
1,230.38.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel, the world's largest steelmaker, was the day's
most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to an estimated 520
million shares from Monday's 398.83 million.
</P>
<P>
Stocks rose across the board, even in recession-hit sectors
such as construction, machinery and steel, traders said.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei's five-day winning streak is its longest since
mid-January, when it closed higher for six consecutive trading
days. The index has now gained more than 770 points since last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The dollar sank to 140 yen during the afternoon trading in
Tokyo amid rumors of a future joint intervention by Japan, the
United States and China to buy the yen.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the rumors, along with more signs that Japan will
unveil a solution for its bad loan mess by Thursday, helped bring
foreign investors back to the stock market.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,333 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
outweighed losers 1,041 to 137. 
</P>
</TEXT>
