<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Assistance For Water Plant In Southwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Work began on a large water plant
being built with Japanese government loans began over the weekend
on the western outskirts of Guiyang, the capital city of Guizhou
Province with 1.2 million residents and an industrial center in
southwestern China.
</P>
<P>
The project will cost 1.07 billion yuan (129 million US
dollars), 319 million (38.4 million US dollars) of which will be
covered by 5.5 billion yen worth of Japanese loans transferred
through the Export-Import Bank, local sources say.
</P>
<P>
Guiyang now has five waterworks, with a combined daily water
capacity of 480,000 cu.m., but this has fallen far short of local
industrial production and individual needs because of rapid
economic and population growth.
</P>
<P>
The new water plant will have a designed daily capacity of
400,000 tons and will include transport, purification, and
distribution facilities.
</P>
<P>
The entire project will take four years to complete. By the
year 2001, the daily capacity of Guiyang Water Supply Corporation
will double, thus greatly helping ease the city's supply problems,
local officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
