<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Joins COMESA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has officially joined the
Common Markets for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) as COMESA
leaders endorsed its membership at their third summit Monday in
Kinshasa, capital of the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
Host President Laurent Kabila and his five counterparts --
Daniel arap Moi of Kenya, Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe, Sam Nujoma
of Namibia, Bakili Muluzi of Malawi, Frederick Chiluba of Zambia
and Pierre Buyoya of Burundi attended the one-day meeting, the
East African Standard reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Also present were Uganda's First Deputy Prime Minister Eriya
Kategaya and a senior minister from Swaziland. At the summit,
Kabila replaced Chiluba as the new rotating COMESA chairman.
</P>
<P>
Issues like free trade, transport, communications and
investment are high on the agenda at the conference.
</P>
<P>
Kabila called for closer economic cooperation among African
nations in order to foster a stronger regional body.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba told the summit that unless African countries strive
to be export oriented rather than producers of raw materials,
they risked being marginalized by the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
COMESA's acting Secretary-General Erastus Mwencha said the
group's member states are confronted with a huge debt burden.
</P>
<P>
"Worse still our region is in dire need for investment
resources for infrastructure, the productive sector, education,
health... It is estimated that on an annual basis, COMESA region
will require in excess 50 billion U.S. Dollars for investment,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Formed in 1994, COMESA groups 19 African states, which have
agreed to promote regional integration through trade development
and common markets. The region has a potential market of over
300 million people.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Presidents of Kenya and Burundi held talks over the
peace process in and the economic sanctions imposed on Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Moi also held separate bilateral talks with
Nujoma and Kabila. Moi is set to come back Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
