<HEADLINE> Estrada Sworn in as Philippine President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President-Elect Joseph
Ejercito Estrada was sworn in Tuesday noon as the country's 13th
president to replace Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Chief Justice Andres Narvasa administrated the oath of office
to Estrada inside historic Barasain Church in Malolos city,
capital of Bulacan Province.
</P>
<P>
After he signed the oath of office, Estrada, 61, held aloft the
document, then bowed to the crowd assembled inside the church.
</P>
<P>
Estrada's oath taking was witnessed by his wife, Loi; his
mother Mary Marcelo De Ejercito; his predecessor, former President
Fidel Ramos; former President Corazon Aquino; members of the
Supreme Court; congressmen and cabinet members.
</P>
<P>
As soon as Estrada finished his oath, the Armed Forces of the
Philippines provided a 21-gun salute, while the church bells
pealed.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, who won an easy victory in the May 11 elections, will
serve a single six-year term.
</P>
<P>
Before the inauguration of Estrada, Senator Gloria
Macapagal-Arroyo was sworn in as vice president.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, who had served as the country's vice president since
1992, will deliver his inaugural speech here Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
