<HEADLINE> New Philippine Cabinet Sworn Into Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
swore into office his 22-member cabinet here hours after he was
inaugurated the country's 13th president at noon Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, who has vowed to crack down on rampant criminal
syndicates in the country, proclaimed himself concurrent secretary
of the Interior and Local Government.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo of the former ruling
Lakas-NUCD (National Union of Christian Democrats) party was named
to head the Department of Social Welfare and Development.
</P>
<P>
Estrada's cabinet was headed by Executive Secretary Ronaldo
Zamora, former member of the House of Representatives and a close
aide of Estrada.
</P>
<P>
Banker Edgardo Espiritu was appointed finance secretary and
former senator Orlando Mercado, former chairman of the Senate
Defense Committee, was designated defense secretary.
</P>
<P>
Three cabinet members of the former government retained their
posts. They are Foreign Affairs Secretary Domingo Siazon, Public
Works and Highways Secretary Gregorio Vigilar, and Science and
Technology Secretary William Padolina.
</P>
<P>
The 61-year-old Estrada, former action movie star, was sworn in
at Barasoain Church in Malolos city near Manila to succeed former
President Fidel Ramos. He will deliver his inaugural speech late
Tuesday afternoon in Manila.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, who was elected president in the 1992 elections, was
banned from running for re-election after his
constitutionally-mandated single six-year term expired at noon
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, who emerged a runaway winner in the May 11
presidential polls, has promised to give priority to fighting
poverty, guaranteeing food security, revitalizing agricultural
sector, and restoring peace and order in the country.
</P>
<P>
Estrada had been vice president for six years since 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
