<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul Proposes Joint Sub Incident Probe With Pyongyang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 30 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
Tuesday directed his cabinet to propose a joint investigation with
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) into the latter's
submarine incident.
</P>
<P>
A government statement said the joint investigation proposed by
the president is designed to identify the cause of the incident.
</P>
<P>
The directive came from the president after the DPRK accused
South Korea of being inhuman in treating the incident which
claimed lives of the nine crewmen inside the submarine.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, the DPRK urged South Korea to return the
submarine and the corpses of the crewmen and condemned Seoul's
description of the submarine incident as being on an espionage
mission.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK also asked South Korea to shoulder the responsibility
for the death of the nine crewmen as it failed to take
humanitarian action to rescue the submarine and its crewmen.
</P>
<P>
On June 22, a DPRK submarine was caught by the South Korean
Navy after it was spotted entangled in a fishing dragnet in the
East Sea (Sea of Japan), some 18 kilometers off the South Korean
city of Solcho.
</P>
<P>
All nine crewmen aboard were found shot to death or committed
suicide when the submarine was opened four days later.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean military authorities said the DPRK sub
incident "on an espionage mission" was a clear violation of South
Korean waters against the Armistice Agreement signed in 1953 and
the South-North basic relations agreement reached in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK, however, claimed that the vessel strayed off course
from engine troubles during a routine military exercise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Banks Raise Rates Amid Rand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Fears that South Africa
faced an economic disaster resurfaced Monday after three major
banks raised their prime overdraft rates by two percentage
points, national newspapers reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
By Monday evening, First National Bank, Standard Bank and
Nedcor had announced increases in their prime rates to 22.25
percent, but kept mortgage rates unchanged for the time being at
20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The hikes followed Monday's rise in the Reserve Bank's repo
rate, the rate at which it lends to banks, to 20.08 percent from
Friday's 18.31 percent in a bid to protect the Rand.
</P>
<P>
The raising of interest rates is a bitter blow to the
government's plans to provide a better life for the country's
poor, as increased lending rates stifle borrowing and growth.
</P>
<P>
On Monday morning the Rand again crashed to record lows
against the major currencies.
</P>
<P>
Shell-shocked traders watched as the currency plummeted,
hitting 6.17 to the U.S. Dollar before subsiding to 5.92 Rand at
the end of the day. The Rand has lost almost 22 percent its value
this year and 7.5 percent in the past week.
</P>
<P>
Against the British Pound, it closed at 9.83 after breaking
the 10 Rand barrier in early trading.
</P>
<P>
The stock exchange and the bond market took a hammering as the
Rand weakened, with financial shares shedding 3.8 percent as
interest rates jitters gripped the markets.
</P>
<P>
If prolonged, the high interest rates could virtually wipe out
economic growth this year and eat a huge chunk out of next year's
growth rate, which was expected to be robust, economists said.
</P>
<P>
They now put growth at about one percent or less for this year
and at two to three percent for next year, down from initial
expectations of about two percent this year and three to four
percent next year.
</P>
<P>
However, government officials tried to put a brave face on
things, emphasizing the positive effects of a weak Rand on the
balance of payments and expressing hope that the situation would
be reversed in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Finance Ministry Director-General Maria Ramos acknowledged
that government's economic growth rate estimate of three percent
for the fiscal year, on which the budget was based, was under
threat.
</P>
<P>
"We will take stock of things and do the number once calm has
returned to the markets. There is a need for a longer-term
perspective," Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
The weaker Rand has pushed up the Rand price of gold, and the
country's gold mines, which were recently contemplating closures
and massive layoffs, are now expected to turn in good
performance.
</P>
<P>
The plunging currency has also made South Africa a cheap
destination for tourists.
</P>
<P>
An economist said the depressing effects of high interest
rates would be moderated by the stimulus to exports from a weak
Rand. "The rise in rates will ensure the competitive advantage of
a weak Rand is not eroded by inflation."
</P>
<P>
But others said the country could not expect too much from
exports, with demand drying up in Asia and Africa and commodity
prices falling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
