<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rising Tea Prices to Boost Malawi Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Malawi beleaguered economy could
get some help from rising world tea prices resulting from
decreased production of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Currently Malawi tea can fetch 1.48 U.S. Dollars per kilogram
compared to 0.99 Dollars in 1997 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the Netherlands have found that Malawi tea is a
good substitute for that of Kenya, the tea production of which
has been hit by a severe drought.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 Malawi produced 43,900 tons of tea, 18 percent higher
than 1996.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary forecasts put this year's output at 44,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
World consumption is expected to increase until the end of the
decade, and prices for Malawi tea are likely to continue firming.
</P>
<P>
Tea is Malawi's second biggest foreign exchange earner. Its
main export of tobacco is suffering from very low prices.
</P>
<P>
Tea exports earned the country 44 million Dollars in 1997
compared with 20 million Dollars in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
