<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Economic Growth Falls: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Africa's economy expanded by 3.7
percent last year, lower than the growth rate of five percent in
the previous year, a survey reaching here says.
</P>
<P>
However, economies in certain African countries grew faster,
the East African Standard newspaper Tuesday quoted the survey as
reporting.
</P>
<P>
Uganda again set the pace with seven percent expansion while
Cameroun, Cote d'Ivoire, Sudan and Tunisia had their economies
growing by between five to six percent, said the report.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey from the Worldwatch Institute,
Africa's economic growth rate is much lower than Asia's which
reached 7.6 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the world economy expanded from 28 trillion U.S.
Dollars in 1996 to 29.1 trillion Dollars last year, up by 4.1
percent and marking the fourth consecutive year of growth at four
percent or more.
</P>
<P>
The south Asian sub-continent, led by India with a growth rate
of 6.6 percent, racked up an overall growth of roughly six
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Economy in advanced industrial countries expanded at three
percent last year. The United States and Canada led the major
industrial states with growth in their economies of 3.7 percent
each.
</P>
<P>
The world trade increased by 4.4 percent to 5.9 trillion
Dollars last year when exports by developing countries grew at
6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The proportion that included exports of minerals and
agricultural items (primary products) from the third world
declined precipitously from 80 percent in 1980 to 40 percent in
1996.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, manufactured goods as a proportion of
developing nations' exports shot up from 20 to 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Trade trends are still dominated by the United States, Japan
and the European Union, but the World Bank projects that in
future they will be set by the "big five" developing nations --
China, India, Indonesia, Brazil and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The five account for more than half of the world's population,
but only nine percent of world's exports. This share will explode
to 25-40 percent by 2020, the World Bank predicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
