<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Remains Largest Potential Market On Earth (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Wang Yuncai, Yan Wenbin
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- China is universally regarded as
the world's largest emerging market, if its high economic growth
rate is maintained, but for the past few years, it has not had the
fiscal strength to make fresh investment, so some Westerners have
mistaken the country as "a big nation but a small market".
</P>
<P>
However, a market research report from the State Council's
Research and Development Center says that the market potential has
gradually become a reality.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Bank, in the next ten years, China's
economy will grow at 8 percent and China will be the world's
largest investment market, with gross fixed assets investment at
around 1.5 trillion U.S. dollars for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The State Statistics Bureau (SSB) says that consumer spending
in China has been growing at 3 to 4 percentage points more than
the GDP since 1996, and analysts predict that China's economy will
recover later this year or early next year in the wake of
increased investment. This will in turn drive consumer spending
and turn China into the world's largest consumer goods market.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Wang Wei, of the Development and Research Center's Market
Research Institute, attributes the lack of consumer power and the
rate of redundancy in some industries to the large number of
identical projects in different locations in the past, but says
this does not suggest any change in China's market capacity.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Wang Yuan, a prominent economist, says that China is one of
the few countries with a high level of savings, higher even than
the level of the early 1990s in Japan and in the Republic of Korea
(ROK), according to IMF. The number of households in China with
incomes above 50,000 yuan annually is equivalent to that of a
moderately-developed European country.
</P>
<P>
In fact, overseas investors have benefited from China's huge
market. At present, 68 percent of the equipment, 70 percent of the
automobile parts, a vast majority of precision, digital machine
tools, and 95 percent of the cordless telephones for China's fixed
assets investment are bought overseas.
</P>
<P>
Motorola alone has 2.7 billion U.S. dollars worth of sales
annually in China, accounting for over 70 percent of China's
market share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
