<HEADLINE> Chinese City Bans Harmful Detergents And Leaded Gasoline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Hangzhou, the capital of east
China's Zhejiang Province imposed a ban on the sale or use of
detergents containing phosphorus and leaded gasoline, effective
December 1st.
</P>
<P>
The city uses 2,000 to 3,000 tons of phosphorus-containing
washing powder, so the use of phosphorus-free detergent is
expected to reduce the amount of phosphorus in waste water
considerably.
</P>
<P>
"This is part of our effort to keep Taihu Lake from being
polluted, and we will extend the practice to rural areas," said Xu
Jikang, of the city's Environmental Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The leaded gas ban is expected to improve the air quality in
the city, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
