<HEADLINE> Romanian Officials Ordered to Declare Intelligence Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 29 (Xinhua) -- All Romanian officials working
with the Intelligence Agency, Interior Ministry and Defense
Ministry have been ordered to furnish the Supreme Defense Council
with their personal records to see whether they had cooperated
with the former intelligence agency.
</P>
<P>
The order, issued on Monday at a special meeting of the
council, asked the Intelligence Agency to hand over all the
records to the council within 10 days, according to the Romanian
news agency Agentie De Presa.
</P>
<P>
Those who had cooperated with the former intelligence agency
will be dismissed from office.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the leaders of the ruling parties and some parliament
members and government officials were accused of having signed
agreements with the former intelligence agency to keep watch over
their colleagues, superiors and subordinates.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister, Francisc Baranyi, and Chairman of the
Parliamentary Commission for the Control of Foreign Information
Service, Adrian Vilau, were forced to resign for this reason
respectively on June 19 and 29.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Radu Vasile has requested all cabinet members to
make a written statement on their past. He emphasized that any
minister who had cooperated with the former intelligence agency
must leave the government.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Defense Council comprises the president, prime
minister, defense minister, interior minister, foreign minister,
industry and trade minister, intelligency agency director and
presidential security adviser. 
</P>
</TEXT>
