<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt's Current Account Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government's current
account improved from a deficit of 93 million U.S. Dollars in the
year ending April 1997 to a deficit of 39 million Dollars in the
year ending April 1998, the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) said.
</P>
<P>
The improvement in the current account is attributed to the
services account surplus which rose by 952 million Dollars due to
the reduction in interest rate payments by 97 million Dollars,
Tuesday's East African Standard quoted latest CBK data as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the government's capital account declined from
surplus of 516 million Dollars in the year to last April to a
deficit of 89 million Dollars in the year to this April.
</P>
<P>
The deterioration is caused by the reduction in the official
medium and long term net capital flows following the halt of the
balance of payments by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and
the drop in short-term capital inflow by about 483 million
Dollars from May 1997 to April 1998.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, gross official foreign exchange reserves fell from
1,064 million Dollars covering 4.1 months of imports to 867
million Dollars or 3.3 months of import cover in April 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
