<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coal Mine Laid-offs Find New Jobs  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 30 (Xinhua) -- When Wang Jianguo lost his job as
a coal miner in north China's Shanxi Province a year ago he found
it very difficult to support his family on a monthly allowance of
little more than 100 yuan.
</P>
<P>
To eke out a living, Wang had to sell clothing by wholesale and
do bits of tough physical labor for a difficult period of time.
The results were not very satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
But now he has a permanent job on a highway construction crew,
where his experience in digging holes in a mine has come in
handy. Standing there at the construction site in hard-hat and
overalls, Wang says, "I need to treasure this job opportunity and
guarantee both quality and quantity."
</P>
<P>
The Xishan Coal and Electric Group, where Wang used to work, is
a very large state-owned coal mine with an annual production
capacity of 26 million tons. But, it has dismissed more than 2,000
employees since early last year as a result of falling sales and
loan defaults, the group's chairman, Du Fuxin, explains.
</P>
<P>
In Shanxi, China's largest coal producing province as a whole,
over 130,000 coal miners, most of whom were engaged in non-mining
work, have been laid off in the wake of scaled-down production.
</P>
<P>
To provide new jobs for laid-off coal miners, the provincial
government has built a 30,000-member highway construction corps
consisting of eight teams because China plans to spend 500 billion
yuan on highway construction in the next three years, and Shanxi's
investment on highway will be 30 billion yuan. This is a new
opportunity for unemployed coal miners, says Wang Jiren, director
of the Shanxi Coal Industry Department.
</P>
<P>
These miner-road crew are working on a 7.2-km highway near
Taiyuan, Shanxi's capital, and will work on expressways to
Taiyuan, Datong, and Jiaozuo afterwards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coal Mine Laid-offs Find New Jobs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Coal mining is a major industry for Shanxi, which is a "sea of
coal". It has eight key state-owned coal mines with a million
employees altogether, whose products are handled by a unified
distribution system.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi has 220 billion tons of coal reserves and produces more
than 300 million tons a year, a quarter of China's output. Over
200 million tons of the province's coal are transported to other
parts of the country and accounts for 80 percent of China's total
coal shipments.
</P>
<P>
The restructuring of state-owned enterprises and the
introduction of a more modern system have meant mechanization and
improvements in the mines. The drive to cut the labor force and
improve efficiency allowed the money-losing industry to get out
of red for the first time in 1997. It also left hundreds of
thousands of coal miners jobless.
</P>
<P>
The laid-off miners have been used for non-mining work, which
resulted in more than 3 billion yuan worth of output value last
year and is expected to match the mining industry in output value
by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
In addition to construction work, the former coal mine
employees have been encouraged to work for township-run mines or
to get involved in high-tech agriculture or other trades over the
past six years.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi has a seventh of China's coal miners and it has played a
vital role in this restructuring. Its successful experiment in
exploring new avenues of employment for miners should be tried in
other provinces, says Ma Deqing, a department head in China's
former Coal Industry Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan, C'Wealth Chief to Meet Nigerian Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- It would be a very busy day Tuesday
for General Abdulsalam Abubakar who is to meet with United
Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan and the Commonwealth
Secretary-General Chief Emeka Anyaoku in the capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
A foreign ministry statement said that Annan, who arrived in
Abuja Monday noon for a four-day visit, is expected to discuss
issues of common interest to the U.N. and Nigeria, including the
maintenance of sub-regional peace and security.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between General Abubakar and Anyaoku, who arrived
Sunday, will border on issues of interest between Nigeria and the
Commonwealth, especially the continued suspension of the country
from the organization, New Nigerian reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The visit of Annan and Anyaoku, following that of British
Foreign Office Minister Tony Lloyd who was in Nigeria last week
on behalf of the European Union, is expected to help break the
diplomatic isolation Nigeria has been faced with since 1993 when
the Western world imposed sanctions on the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a high-powered delegation from the United States
headed by Under-Secretary Thomas Pickering, is also expected to
be in Nigeria next week for talks with General Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
The West has seen the sudden death of Nigeria's former
military leader General Sani Abacha as an opportunity to improve
relations with the most populous black country in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Western countries hope Abacha's successor, General Abubakar
would handle the military government's transition to civil rule
program in a way that would bring democracy to the country.
</P>
