<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Working to Boost Crop Yields on Arid Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists are working on
developing a water-saving technique that could increase grain
output by 10 percent without using a drop of water more for
irrigation.
</P>
<P>
With 50 million yuan (6 million U.S. dollars) in funds from
the central government annually, more than 4,000 scientists are
studying the technique which is believed to markedly increase
grain output in irrigated areas.
</P>
<P>
In the Yangling High-Tech Demonstration Zone -- China's "agro
silicon valley" in northwest China's Shaanxi Province, scientists
are seen working on water-saving and other dry farming
techniques. Their study fields include drought-resistant crops,
seed breeding, water-saving irrigation and dry farming techniques,
farm machinery for arid land, and water resource development.
</P>
<P>
Shan Lun, academician of the Chinese Academy of Engineering and
an arid land development specialist, says that the research
programs will play a key role in increased grain outputs in
northern China in the 21st century and will demonstrate
agricultural development in arid areas.
</P>
<P>
Hailing it an important move to build China's own bread basket,
Vice-Premier Li Lanqing called the research China's "strategic
decision".
</P>
<P>
A unique water-saving irrigation technique developed by
scientists there that can reduce the amount of irrigation water by
33 percent has already been used in Shaanxi and Gansu provinces
and the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Another program for sustainable development of the Loess
Plateau of scientists at the agro silicon valley has greatly
improved the ecology in many parts of northwestern China and
brought profits of as much as 4 billion yuan in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
China suffers from water shortages and has only 100 million
hectares of arable land for its 1.2 billion people.
</P>
<P>
However, specialists believed that the arid and semi-arid areas
have great grain-growing potential at a time when intensive
farming in southern China has made it difficult to increase crop
output there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
