<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Technology Being Used To Protect Confucius' Temple </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 30 (Xinhua) -- China is using new technology to
protect cultural relics in the city of Qufu in China's Shandong
Province, the birthplace of Confucius, the philosopher and
educator who lived about 2,500 years ago.
</P>
<P>
A 5-million-yuan (about 600,000 US dollars) computer system has
been installed to help protect relics in the Temple, Mausoleum,
and Manor house of his descendants.
</P>
<P>
Files of more than 10,000 relics like pottery, jades, bronze
ware, ivory carvings, ancient books, and paintings housed in the
temple, mausoleum and manor can be seen on a computer system, thus
avoiding damage caused by direct contact, according to Li Bozhu,
who developed the system.
</P>
<P>
He says they plan to include descriptions of all cultural
relics, tablet inscriptions, ancient trees, and buildings in Qufu
in the system in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Qufu has at least 200 ancient buildings, 100,000 ancient tombs,
17,000 ancient trees, 1,000 stone engravings, and 5,000 tablet
inscriptions that date back as early as the Han Dynasty (206
B.C.-220 A.D.). The Temple, Mausoleum, and Manor house are on the
World Cultural Heritage list.
</P>
<P>
Qufu has spent 6.5 million yuan on fire and theft protection
for the buildings in recent years, according to Kong Xianglin, a
descendent of Confucius who is head of the cultural relics
protection committee of Qufu.
</P>
<P>
The city has also built a storehouse for relics that is worth 9
million yuan and is air-conditioned and has an alarm and
sprinkling system for fires.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
