<HEADLINE> Economic Integration In Eastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, June 30 (Xinhua) - The Shanghai Light Industry
Holding Group recently signed an agreement here with the city of
Ruijin in China's Jiangxi Province for the world's largest
sewing machine needle factory as yet another example of the
transfer of labor intensive projects from developed Chinese cities
and provinces to less-developed areas in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Early this month at a trade fair, Jiangxi, in east China,
signed 440 contracts with Shanghai and the coastal provinces of
Zhejiang, Jiangsu, and Fujian for agriculture, industry, and
infrastructure projects worth five billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Fujian and Jiangsu also held trade fairs to try to attract
investment from Shanghai and provided 50 major projects, worth 4
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, China decided to speed up economic development of the
Yangtze River Delta and eastern China, with Shanghai as the main
engine driving the development. The East has become the country's
most developed area and accounts for 40 percent of China's exports
and 46 percent of its foreign capital accounts.
</P>
<P>
Economists say that economic cooperation in the East needs to
increase and the best use of their different economic advantages
made.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu, Zhejiang, Shandong, Anhui, Fujian, and Jiangxi have
thousands of companies in Shanghai, with registered capital
exceeding 10 billion yuan, and Shanghai's investment in those six
provinces accounts for 60 percent of its investment outside the
city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
