<HEADLINE> Western China Claims Oldest Amphibian With A Tail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese biologist says that a
salamander living in remote mountain streams of western China may
be the oldest amphibian with a tail in existence.
</P>
<P>
The animal, Ranodon Sibiricus, was discovered 8 years ago in
the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, where it has lived for over
300 million years, according to Wang Xiuling, a professor at
Xinjiang Teachers' University.
</P>
<P>
She says, however, that biologists have yet to find fossils
that could support this claim, although fossils of other
salamanders have been found in the region.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 of the animals now live in three streams at an
altitude of about 2,500 meters above sea level, Wang says, and
local biologists are looking for more of the rare animals in a
stream 3,200 meters above sea level.
</P>
<P>
The ancient amphibian lives only in western China and eastern
Kazakhstan and provides important information for zoology and
species evolution.
</P>
<P>
Wang and her colleagues have successfully bred the amphibian
since 1990 and are now trying to move it to other places with more
friendly environmental conditions for better protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guizhou Plans to Ease Water Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Guizhou Province
aims to resolve its drinking water shortage by the end of this
century.
</P>
<P>
A drinking-water shortage has been the major hindrance to the
province's development, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The shortage is mainly caused by the karst topography, which
takes up nearly 70 percent of the province.
</P>
<P>
"The vegetation is poor here because of the karst topography,
and that results in a poor water-reservation capacity," a local
expert said.
</P>
<P>
The province, one of China's poorest regions, has spent 263
million yuan in the past one and half years to quench the
drinking-water shortage of some 980,000 people and 680,000
livestocks.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the province plans to spend a huge amount of
money every year to ease the water shortage by the end of this
century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
