<HEADLINE> Bird Selected to Hall of Fame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Larry Bird, a three-time NBA
Most Valuable Player who was named NBA Coach of the Year, was
selected into the Basketball Hall of Fame on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Bird, who was on the league's 50 greatest players list in 1996,
and coached the Indian Pacers to the runner up in the Eastern
Conference this season, was among six other people to gain the
honor.
</P>
<P>
Bird, a 12-time All-Star, held or shared 27 Celtics records by
the time he retired in 1992, and led the team to NBA titles in
1981, 1984, 1986.
</P>
<P>
He also captured league MVP honors from 1984 to 1986, and was
MVP of the NBA Finals in 1981 and 1986. During his player career,
Boston won 10 Atlantic Division titles, had six seasons of 60-plus
wins and topped the 50-win mark 12 times.
</P>
<P>
In his first year as a head coach this past season, the Paces
scored the second-best record in the conference with 58 wins and
24 losses.
</P>
<P>
The other six persons who entered the Hall of Fame are former
Harlem Globetrotter great Marques Haynes, ex-Rochester Royal and
Boston Celtic Arnie Risen, longtime NBA coach Alex Hannum,
University of Texas women's coach Jody Conradt, Yugoslav coach
Aleksandar Nikolic and Atlanta Hawks coach Lenny Wilkens. 
</P>
