<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder (2): Hong Kong - Int'l Financial Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is a major
international financial center, thanks to its favorable
geographical position, bridging the time gap between North America
and Europe, and its strong links with the Chinese inland areas and
other parts of Asia.
</P>
<P>
The absence of any restriction on capital flows is also an
important factor for the development of the Hong Kong financial
industry.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is the world's fifth largest banking center in terms
of the volume of external banking transactions. It has a very
strong presence of international institutions. Some 500 banks and
deposit-taking companies from 43 countries and regions have
operations here, including 82 of the world's top 100 banks.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has a mature and active foreign exchange market,
which ranks the fifth in the world and forms an integral part of
the global market.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is the world's fourth largest gold bullion market.
Its stock market is Asia's second largest in terms of market
capitalization and ranks the seventh in the world. The stock
market acts as an important funding source for companies in Asia,
particularly for those Chinese enterprises seeking overseas
investment.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's derivative market is among Asia's largest,
reflecting the increased sophistication of its financial markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder (3): Hong Kong - Int'l Trading Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong economy is highly
externally oriented and dependent on trade with the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
The city was placed the world's eighth largest trading entity
in 1997 by the World Trade Organization (WTO), accounting for 3.6
percent of world total trade.
</P>
<P>
The value of Hong Kong's total merchandise trade amounted to
3,071 billion HK dollars (393.7 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997, or
around 230 percent of the GDP for the year.
</P>
<P>
This indicated that Hong Kong's position as an international
trading center has been well preserved after the handover. The
Basic Law guarantees continuation of Hong Kong's economic and
trading system, the free movement of goods and capital and its
status as a free port and separate customs territory.
</P>
<P>
The constitutional document of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region of China also provides that Hong Kong may
continue to participate in relevant international trade
organizations and agreements. Hong Kong is now a member of the
WTO, the World Customs Organization and the Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC).
</P>
<P>
The year 1997 witnessed modest export growth of Hong Kong.
Government figures showed that the value of total exports in the
whole year of 1997 stood at 1,455.9 billion HK dollars (186.6
billion U.S. dollars), up 4.2 percent over the same period of the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Re-exports made up 85 percent of the value of total export,
reflecting the continued importance of Hong Kong as an entrepot
for China's mainland, Hong Kong's number one trading partner.
</P>
<P>
The value of re-exports in 1997 was 1,244.5 billion HK dollars
(159.6 billion U.S. dollars), 5 percent higher, while the value of
domestic exports, at 211.4 billion HK dollars (27.1 billion U.S.
dollars), dipped slightly by 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The value of imports increased by 5.2 percent to 1,615.1
billion HK dollars (207.1 billion U.S. dollars). Therefore a
visible trade deficit of 159.1 billion HK dollars (20.4 billion
U.S. dollars), equivalent to 9.9 percent of the value of imports,
was recorded for 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese mainland accounted for one-third of Hong Kong's
total merchandise trade, followed by the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Dampened by the regional financial crisis and a major downturn
in the tourism industry, Hong Kong's export of services showed
almost no increase in 1997 against the previous year, following an
8.6 percent increase for the whole of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder (5): Hong Kong - Information Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong, the regional entrepot
of finance and trade, is marked by the high degree of import and
application of advanced technology, particularly that related to
information industry.
</P>
<P>
Taking advantage of its status of free port, Hong Kong
maintains economic links with over 100 countries and regions,
making it a pivot of information, and now it is trying to build
itself into "the most informed city in the world" as described by
the Hong Kong Telecom.
</P>
<P>
Wired by satellite, optical fibers, cables, microwaves and
other media, Hong Kong has formed an information network,
particularly economic information network, both locally and
globally.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is the first major city in the world to have a fully
digitized telephone network and the amount of its outgoing
international phone calls is much higher than both the United
States and Japan. Hong Kong now has a telecommunications network
comprising over 300,000 kilometers of optical fiber.
</P>
<P>
About one-sixth of Hong Kong's population or 1.1 million people
have subscribed to paging services -- the highest per-capita rate
in the world. And a total of over 1 million subscribers to
cellular phone services also is among the highest levels of
penetration in the world.
</P>
<P>
A recent market survey showed that the home penetration rate of
PC is over 50 percent and there are more than 850,000 Internet
users in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In March, the world's first-ever interactive TV (iTV) was
launched in Hong Kong, making it possible for people to see films,
listen to music or deal with financial affairs at any time with
clicks of a few buttons at home. And just two weeks ago, the
Internet service was added to the iTV network, enabling users to
get access to the worldwide web at a surprisingly high speed.
</P>
<P>
An international conference on the future of information and
communications technology in Asia had just concluded in Hong Kong.
Organizers of the conference said the city provides a dynamic,
technology-rich environment, whose government sees technology as a
critical component of Hong Kong's successful future. Also, the
regional hub provides an open location in which to examine the
various models of technology throughout Asia.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1960s, Hong Kong has brought in U.S. and Japanese
investment in electronic industry, which has become the second
largest industry in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Technology advancement is a key factor of economic growth in
Hong Kong. A research on the manufacturing sector in Hong Kong
shows that technology development accounted for an average of 42.9
percent in the sector's production during the period of 1969 to
1982.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's technology development is market-oriented and
characterized by high efficiency. For instance, it usually takes a
mere three months for general electronics and plastics from
product design to production.
</P>
<P>
There are several prestigious academic institutions in Hong
Kong, including Hong Kong University, the Chinese University of
Hong Kong, Hong Kong University of Science and Technology, and
they are well equipped and have absorbed talents from all over the
world.
</P>
<P>
Political and social stability ensures Hong Kong favorable
working and living conditions. In addition, Hong Kong's ability to
develop technology-rich products has been well-complimented by the
abundant outcome of the ever-increasing scientific research in
China's inland areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
