<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Domestic Debts Increase in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government's
domestic debts increased to 762.6 billion pesos (19 billion U.S.
dollars) in April, 3 percent higher than in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest report of the Bureau of Treasury, of
the amount, 98.95 percent is real obligations of the national
government, and the rest is contingent liabilities.
</P>
<P>
Real obligations refer to those directly borrowed or assumed by
the national government while contingent liabilities are debts
borrowed by government-owned or controlled corporations and
agencies which are guaranteed by the government.
</P>
<P>
The report said that of the real obligations, 752.2 billion
pesos are direct loans of the national government, most of which
were borrowed in the form of government securities such as
Treasury bills and bonds.
</P>
<P>
As of April, the report said, the total securities issued by
the government amounted to 460.3 billion pesos (11.5 billion
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
