<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Passes Finance Bill for New Fiscal Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's Jatiya Sangsad, the
country's parliament, passed the Finance Bill 1998 for the 1998-99
fiscal year beginning July 1, press reports here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Bill, to come into effect on July 1, was adopted
after Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria declared amendments to
the tax measures proposed in the new budget, including the
withdrawal or reduction of taxes, duties and value-added taxes on
16 items.
</P>
<P>
Most of the tax and duty reductions are on raw materials of
certain local industries such as specialized textiles, power looms
and henolic resin and on items like bicycle and rickshaw spare
parts, cement and medical and surgical equipment used by ordinary
people, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal of proposals for enhanced taxes and duties were
based on discussions on the budget by the opposition members of
parliament, suggestions offered by different business bodies and
comments made in newspapers, the fiancee minister told the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Withdrawal or reduction of the new taxation proposals would
cause a revenue loss of more than 277 million taka (about 6
million U.S. dollars) and the government would make good the loss
by initiating appropriate administrative measures, he said.
</P>
<P>
The budget for the new financial year is expected to be passed
by the parliament Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
