<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke - UN Promises Help in Funding for Cambodian Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The UN special representative
of the secretary-general, Lakhan Mehrohtra, pledged Monday that
the United Nations will do its best to help raise funds for
specific tasks related to Cambodia's elections.
</P>
<P>
Mehrohtra made the remarks during a meeting with members of
Cambodia's National Election Committee (NEC) on election-related
issues. The world body estimated that some 3.7 million
U.S. dollars was still needed by the NEC.
</P>
<P>
The UN envoy praised the NEC's work so far and agreed with NEC
Chairman HE Chheng Phon that voter education programs were a
priority for both organizations.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP trust fund has garnered two million U.S. dollars for a
voter education campaign. The NEC plans to disseminate the message
that the vote is secret, and that voters should be able to
exercise their democratic rights free from intimidation.
</P>
<P>
The UN raised some concerns about the process on polling day,
emphasizing the need for indelible ink to ensure that no person
can vote twice, and the counting process at commune level.
</P>
<P>
NEC Vice-chairman Kassie Neou said that the contents of at
least three ballot boxes will be mixed together before each count,
but in the vast majority of communes the mix will include many
more than three boxes. Most CECs will cover between four and 33
polling stations.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question by Mehrohtra on how regulations against
bias are enforced in the electronic media, the NEC replied that it
has set up a unit to monitor the air time given to each party.
</P>
<P>
The month-long campaign, which began peacefully on June 25 and
entered its sixth day Tuesday, has so far gone smoothly without
any violence.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's National Assembly election has largely been seen as
a contest between three main parties--the CPP of the influential
Second Prime Minister Hun Sen, the Funcinpec party of the deposed
first prime minister Prince Ranariddh and opposition leader Sam
Rainsy's party named after himself. 
</P>
</TEXT>
