<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE -- Singapore Finance Minister Richard Hu Tsu Tau on
Monday announced a 68-point package of off-budget measures to
boost the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Under the much-anticipated measures, an estimated 2 billion
Singapore dollars will be injected into the economy.
</P>
<P>
The package, covering all areas in the economy, includes
several tax concessions designed to help ease business costs
during the current economic downturn and help local business
obtain working capital in a situation of tight liquidity, the
minister said. (Singapore-Measures-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG -- The latest package released by the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR) government to address the
economic downturn does not depart from the government's
long-standing policy of non-interference with market operations, a
senior SAR official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Officiating at the opening ceremony of the Hong Kong Economic
Forum, Financial Secretary Donald Tsang defended the rescue
package announced last Monday, saying, "We are just responding to
market conditions. Our aim is to facilitate economic adjustment,
not to tamper with normal market activities." (Hong Kong-Economy)
</P>
