<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Sets Up First-Ever Tea Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka is setting up the first
tea museum in the hill capital of Kandy, 115 kilometers from here,
according to tea board sources Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The tea museum is to mark over 100 years of tea production
which has culminated in the country becoming the world's best tea
producer.
</P>
<P>
Tea seeds were introduced to Sri Lanka from China more than 160
years ago. James Taylor, a Briton, planted tea for the first time
on a 20-acre block at Deltota in the hill country in 1867.
</P>
<P>
The museum is being established by the Sri Lankan Planters'
Association in collaboration with the Sri Lanka Tea Board. It will
have on display obsolete machinery and other items of historical
value from field and factory.
</P>
<P>
The sources said daily instruction books of estate managers and
labor muster books over a century old had been discovered. Antique
tea machinery over 100 years old is being restored. A set of
priceless antique photographs has been obtained from England for
the museum.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the tea museum is expected to cost 625,000
U.S. dollars while maintenance costs are expected to exceed 1,000
dollars per month, according to the sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Council Calls for Protection of Children in Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Monday appealed to all parties in armed conflicts to end the
practice of targeting children.
</P>
<P>
The council strongly condemned the targeting of children in
armed conflicts and called on all parties concerned to strictly
comply with their obligations under international law, a
presidential statement said.
</P>
<P>
Recognizing the importance of the mandate of the Special
Representative of the U.N. Secretary-General on Children in Armed
Conflict, the council expressed its support for his activities.
</P>
<P>
Before the statement was issued, Olara Otunnu, the special
representative, drew the council's attention to the somber picture
of children in affected countries.
</P>
<P>
In the last decade, two million children have been killed as a
result of armed conflicts, with more than one million orphaned,
and six million seriously injured or permanently disabled, he said.
</P>
<P>
Another 12 million had been made homeless and 10 million left
with serious psychological trauma.
</P>
<P>
"Children, especially young women, have been made the targets
of rape and other forms of sexual violence on a large scale," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Otunnu, a former Ugandan foreign minister who took the current
U.N. job in 1997, said a quarter of a million young persons under
the age of 18 are estimated to be under arms today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
