<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Three-Year ESAF Credit for the Gambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) Monday approved a three-year credit for Gambia under the
Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF), equivalent to some
27 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The low-interest rate credit is provided in support of the
government's economic program for 1998-2000. The first annual
credit, equivalent to some 9 million dollars, is available in two
equal semiannual installments, the first of which is available
immediately.
</P>
<P>
The major economic objectives for 1998-2000 are to achieve real
GDP growth of 4.5 percent to 5 percent a year, keep annual
inflation around 3 percent, reduce the external current account
deficit to less than 10 percent of GDP by the year 2000, and keep
gross official reserves above the equivalent to five months of
imports.
</P>
<P>
Gambia joined the IMF in September 1967. Its quota is some 30
million dollars equivalent and its outstanding use of IMF
financing currently totals about 7.7 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
