<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More College Students Become CPC Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese officials announced today,
on the eve of the 77th anniversary of the Communist Party of China
(CPC), that 4 out of every 100 Chinese college students are
members of the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
The 129,000 college students who are CPC members represent an
increase of 113,000 since 1990, when that was only 0.8 percent
of the students.
</P>
<P>
Among graduate students, 41,000 are Party members, or 26.2
percent of the total, a 4 percent increase since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jianguo, a Ministry of Education official, says that
college students have become more confident about the CPC as a
result of political and social stability, economic growth, an
improved standard of living, and success in foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Academy of Social Sciences says that the 15th Party
Congress, Hong Kong's return, Jiang Zemin's U.S. visit, and
China's actions during the Asian financial crisis have had a
good effect on Chinese youth. And, a course on "Deng Xiaoping
Theory" recently started at Chinese universities has become one of
the most popular.
</P>
<P>
"The course helped me understand what socialism is and how to
build socialism, and to know that the CPC will lead China to a
bright future," says Zhang Jie, a student in the International
Relations Department of Beijing University, where Party members
account for 12 percent of the student body.
</P>
<P>
Many colleges have Marxism societies. At a recent seminar on
Marxism in Beijing University, teachers and students agreed that
though there have been ups and downs, China's reforms and opening
up have proven that Marxism will continue if it improves.
</P>
<P>
Li Wenhai, the president of People's University, says that, in
the 1990s, many colleges have been paying greater attention to
improving morales and have provided students with more
opportunities to better understand society.
</P>
<P>
"Students have more information about reality, and their sense
of social responsibility and patriotic passion have increased," he
says, so more students have applied to join the Party.
</P>
<P>
A fourth to a third of the 3 million students in China's 1,000
universities and colleges have applied, because, in the words of
Cheng Shuihua, a student at Shanghai's Fudan University, "Being a
Party member is the best way for me to devote myself to the
nation."
</P>
<P>
Wang, the Education Ministry official, says that most student
Party members have quick and independent minds and good morale
character, and usually get good grades. Many are good at
organizing social activities.
</P>
<P>
Some of them have volunteered to work in remote,
poverty-stricken areas after graduation, and many have been sought
by big companies, including joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
This year is the 150th anniversary of the "Communist Manifesto"
and the 90th anniversary of Marxism in China, where universities
were the cradle of Communist thought. The CPC was founded in July
1, 1921, with 57 Party members. That number has grown to more than
58 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
