<HEADLINE> U.S. President Clinton Tours Library in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. President Bill
Clinton toured the new site of Shanghai Library this morning and
participated in a round-table discussion, entitled "Shaping China
for the 21st Century," there with local community leaders.
</P>
<P>
The library, built at a cost of 600 million yuan (72.3 million
U.S. dollars), boasts 13 million books and is one of the ten major
buildings in Shanghai. The library was put into use in December of
1996.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the discussion included Bishop Jin Luxian,
Catholic Prelate of Shanghai; Wu Qidi, president of Tongji
University; and Zuo Xuejin, vice-president of Shanghai Academy of
Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
At noon, Clinton will talk with citizens in Shanghai at a radio
call-in show at the Shanghai People's Broadcast Station.
</P>
<P>
Started in October of 1992, the live radio program entitled
"Citizens and Society" is aired five times a week focusing on hot
topics among citizens. Usually, government officials and scholars
are invited to talk with citizens.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, the U.S. president will tour Yuyuan, a famous
tourist attraction in Shanghai, and go shopping there.
</P>
<P>
This afternoon, Clinton will pay a visit to the new site of
Shanghai Museum to see rare and exquisite bronze antiques which
exhibit over 1,500 years of history in the development of bronze
wares from the 18th century BC to the third century BC.
</P>
<P>
According to schedule, Shanghai Mayor Xu Kuangdi will meet with
the U.S. president this evening. 
</P>
