</P>
<P>
"President Clinton's visit to China marks a dialogue
between two major countries in the world, and will have worldwide
impact," said Jean Michel Molin, president of the US-funded
Dole-Tropicana China Beihai Food Corp.
</P>
<P>
The company has leased 3,079 hectares of land in Beihai, a
coastal city in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region,
for orange planting, and a large orange juice plant will be
erected there.
</P>
<P>
With a total investment of nearly 50 million US dollars, it is
currently the largest US-funded agricultural project in China,
said Molin.
</P>
<P>
"As the president of an American business, I feel very good
working in Guangxi. With the support of officials at all levels,
we have no difficulties in developing business here, and our
production keeps growing," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that he was very pleased to know that
President Clinton would also pay a visit to the picturesque city
of Guilin in Guangxi during his China trip.
</P>
<P>
"I never heard of Guangxi before I came here," said Molin.
"Clinton's visit to Guilin will increase the popularity of Guangxi
and help more people to learn about this region."
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the belief that President Clinton's visit
would bring more trade opportunities for both America and China.
</P>
<P>
"I hope more foreign business people will come to invest here,
and experience a different and colorful culture at the same time,"
he concluded.  
