<HEADLINE> Ukraine and Argentina Sign Cooperation Accords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine and Argentina signed Monday
a treaty of friendship and cooperation and also an agreement on
scientific cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The agreements were signed during a two-day visit to Ukraine by
Argentine President Carlos Saul Menem, who became the first leader
from a Latin American country to visit the former Soviet republic.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Menem met with Ukrainian President Leonid
Danilovich Kuchma, First Deputy Prime Minister Anatoly Golubchenko
and Minister of Foreign Affairs Boris Tarasyuk, the official
Ukrainian news agency UKRINFORM reported.
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed the promotion of cooperation in fields
such as foreign trade, metallurgy, energy, agriculture and
military affairs.
</P>
<P>
Menem, who will end his visit on Wednesday, said Argentina will
provide financial assistance to Ukraine for sealing the Chernobyl
Nuclear Power Station. In April, 1986, an explosion in the station
caused serious radioactive damage to many countries and areas.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine leader also stressed his country's support for
Ukraine's entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO), adding
that after his visit he hoped to see trade between the two
countries increase fourfold from the 40 million U.S. dollars worth
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also pledged efforts to strengthen the link
between Black Sea Economic Cooperation Organization (BSECO) and
South American Common Market (SACM). 
</P>
</TEXT>
