<HEADLINE> Indonesian Armed Forces Commander Denies They Still </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Armed Forces (ABRI)
Monday denied that they are still loyal to former President
Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
"ABRI does not receive direct orders or instructions from
former President Soeharto. All of the accusations that ABRI is
under his control are untrue," ABRI Commander/Defense Minister
General Wiranto was quoted by the local press Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
"When he was president, there was a structural relationship as
he was our supreme commander. But now it is clear the structural
relationship no longer exists," Wiranto said.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that he could not avoid maintaining a
"cultural relationship" with Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
He said that as an Indonesian, who adheres to an Eastern
culture, he could not simply discard past good relations with
Soeharto just because the latter is no longer president.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto stepped down on May 21 amid mounting demands for his
resignation as the country was hit by political and economic
crisis. While he holds no official position since stepping down,
speculation continues to circulate that Soeharto retains influence
over ABRI's top brass.
</P>
<P>
According to The Jakarta Post, during most of his public
appearances recently, which have been very few and usually
centered around Friday prayers, Soeharto has been seen accompanied
by a senior ABRI officer. Last Friday, Soeharto attended prayers
at the Army's headquarters in Central Jakarta and met Army Chief
of Staff General Subagyo Hadisiswoyo. 
