<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Poorest Areas to be Lifed Out of Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, June 30 (Xinhua) -- China's three poorest areas, all
located in the northwest, are expected to be free from poverty in
1999 after a senior official in Dingxi, referred to as the
"poorest place on earth", announced today that it will be lifted
from poverty next year.
</P>
<P>
Liu Lijun, deputy commissioner of Gansu Province's Dingxi
Prefecture, said Dingxi will free most of its area from poverty
this year and eradicate poverty next year as part of the Chinese
government's ambitious goal of eradicating poverty by the end of
the century.
</P>
<P>
Following the successful poverty relief effort in the Gansu's
Hexi Prefecture and the determination of Dingxi to eliminate
poverty in 1999, the other area, Xihaigu Prefecture in nearby
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, also announced that it will get rid
of poverty by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
Dingxi, Hexi and Xihaigu, are known as the "three Xi's". Their
380,000 square kilometers account for one of the largest
poverty-stricken areas in China.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, the Chinese government committed itself to eradicating
poverty by the end of the century and analysts say that the
success of the poverty-relief efforts in the three Xi's is vital
to the success of that program. One United Nations representative
who visited Dingxi commented that the success story of the three
Xi's gives new hope for poor regions in other areas.
</P>
<P>
In 1982, the Chinese government decided to allocate 200 million
yuan (24 million U.S. dollars) each year to help the three
prefectures deal with the extreme poverty and worsening ecological
conditions as the first national poverty-relief program.
</P>
<P>
By now, it has put three billion yuan into the program, helping
over three million people there escape poverty. Hexi was the first
to get totally free from poverty and has become a national grain,
cotton, and edible oil center.
</P>
<P>
Owing to the extreme dry conditions, Dingxi for a long time
lacked even basic subsistence conditions, but now, a visitor is
struck by the tree-covered hills, the green terraced fields, and
the dams. Farmers here used to live in cave dwellings, but now
have built brick and tile houses and even some two-story homes.
</P>
<P>
But, one of the most unusual changes is the cistern in the
courtyard of almost every home and in the fields. It is also the
major source of the changes around these parts, where great
changes have taken place, with the number of people living below
the poverty line going from over 1.7 million in 1982 to the
present 472,000, Liu explains.
</P>
<P>
China has about 50 million rural people living below the
poverty line, or about a twentieth of the world's poor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Extend Loans to Small Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will pump 10
billion baht (238 million U.S. dollars) into a fund that will lend
to small and medium-sized manufacturers to ease their cash-flow
problems, the Bangkok Post said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Deputy Prime Minister Supachai
Panitchpakdi as saying the loans would be channeled through the
Export-Import Bank and the Small Industries Finance Corporation
(SIFC).
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry will lend 5 billion baht (119 million
dollars) at low interest rates to the Exim Bank, which will lend
the funds to local trading companies.
</P>
<P>
The trading companies in turn will re-lend the money to smaller
producers whose products they help to distribute overseas.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said at a senior economic ministers' meeting Monday
that the loans would help increase the sales of small and
medium-sized industries by up to 3 billion baht (71.4 million
dollars) this year, 8 billion baht (190 million dollars) next year
and 12 billion baht (285.7 million dollars) in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The other 5 billion baht for the program will come from the
structural adjustment loans funded by the World Bank and the Asian
Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also approved in principle the request of the SIFC
to seek another 1.36 billion baht (32.4 million dollars) for
lending, in addition to the 1.48 billion (35.2 million dollars)
already extended to small manufacturers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
