<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs in Latin American countries in the past few
days.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The Brazilian government has decided to import
420,000 tons of rice from the United States and Asian countries
this year.
</P>
<P>
In 1998 Brazil has to import 2 million tons of rice and 5.9
million tons of wheat to meet high domestic demands resulting from
bad harvest.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Trade between Chile and Peru is expected to
increase 30 percent in 1998, compared with last year.
</P>
<P>
Chile's exports to Peru were worth 347.8 million U.S. dollars,
while its imports from that country were worth 118.5 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil imported 54,900 tons of steel and
derivatives in the first four months of 1998, an increase of 21.2
percent over 1997.
</P>
<P>
The value of the imports amounted to 189 million dollars, 18.1
percent more than that in the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The total deposits in pesos increased by 3.3
percent in May, while the deposits in foreign currency decreased
0.7 percent, the Association of Argentine Banks said.
</P>
<P>
The loans for the private sector increased 0.6 percent, while
the loans for the public sector increased 1.8 percent, and
personal loans increased 0.7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
