<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Consider Expanding Use of "Smart Card" as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) governments will consider expanding the use of a
"smart card" as a formal travel document for their citizens after
they have harmonized their immigration regulations.
</P>
<P>
This was stated by Indonesia's Immigration Directorate General
spokesman H.B. Lapian on the sidelines of an ASEAN immigration
meeting in Batam near Singapore on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Before the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) begins in the year
2003, ASEAN member states should have finalized preparations to
use a common smart card," Lapian was quoted by Antara News Agency
Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The smart card is already in use by citizens of Singapore,
Malaysia and Indonesia to travel between the countries while the
six other ASEAN member countries have had to postpone its use by
their citizens due to lack of skilled human resources and
finances.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore, Brunei, Thailand,
the Philippines, Vietnam, Myanmar and Laos.
</P>
<P>
Lapian said the smart card, functioning as a travel document,
would enable ASEAN member countries to accelerate their region's
economic growth together.
</P>
<P>
The card is also needed in anticipating developments in
intra-ASEAN travel in the globalization and free trade era, he
said, adding that the card's finalization required the ASEAN
governments' political will.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN immigration meeting in Batam, attended by delegates
from all ASEAN member states, was a follow-up of meetings among
ASEAN member countries' immigration authorities in Kuala Lumpur,
Malaysia, and Jakarta last year.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting Monday, Indonesia was elected to chair a
technical working group because the country is supposed to have
experience in using the smart card since July 1994.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fugitive Fujian Province Couple Sought for Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The public security bureau in
Fujian Province are seeking fugitives Gao Xiaoduan and Zhuang
Deshuang, who fled China not long ago, for fraudulently obtaining
100,000 yuan (8,200 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Gao and Zhuang started a knit garment factory in 1992 in Yonghe
Township in the city of Jinjiang, east China's Fujian Province. In
examing their records, police discovered that the couple had left
behind debts of 2.05 million yuan (256,250 U.S. dollars). The
money was borrowed from the local branch of the Agricultural Bank
of China, township and village foundations, and a dozen
individuals.
</P>
<P>
Investigations revealed that Gao Xiaoduan and Zhuang Deshuang
borrowed 100,000 yuan from the Yonghe Township Foundation on May
4, 1995 under the name Zhuang Debao, Zhuang Deshuang's
cousin. Zhuang Deshuang acted as the guarantor.
</P>
<P>
But Zhuang Debao denied that he had ever borrowed from the
foundation and his signature on the receipt was apparently forged
by Gao Xiaoduan.
</P>
<P>
The local public security bureau determined that Gao and Zhuang
had violated the law by collaborating and forging the signature to
get the public funds. The Jinjiang People's Procuratorate has
issued an order of arrest for the fugitive couple.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
