<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Income Tax Exempted for New Foreign Companies in Slovakia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Slovakian government has decided
to offer 10-year income tax exemption to all foreign enterprises
set up in Slovakia in and after 1998.
</P>
<P>
Under the new preferential policy which comes into effect on
July 1, the enterprises which qualify must be manufacturers
spending 300 million Korunas (9.38 million U.S. dollars) to
purchase equipment and exporting 90 percent of their products.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Slovakia saw a gradual increase of direct
foreign investment which reached 1.13 billion dollars in 1997,
39.5 percent up from 1996. The total direct foreign investment
attracted by Slovakia from 1993 to 1997 was 3.58 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Although 1997 saw the largest direct foreign investment in
Slovakia since its independence in 1993, investment was markedly
lower than in its neighbors, including Hungary, Poland and the
Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
The Slovakian government has repeatedly said that it would take
various measures to attract more foreign investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
