<HEADLINE> Colombian Government, Liberation Army to Resume Peace Talks. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian National
Liberation Army and the Colombian government signed an agreement
on peace talks in Mein, Germany, on Monday, the radio station RCN
reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the National Liberation Army and the
government's National Council for the Peace (CNP) will continue
negotiations in Germany.
</P>
<P>
They will also discuss the possibility of holding a national
convention for the final settlement of the hostilities in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Sabas Pretel and Jaime Bernal of
the CNP and Milton Hernandez and Pablo Beltran of the National
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between the government and the National Liberation
Army was part of the "Pre-Agreement of Viana Palace" signed last
February in Madrid, Spain. But the government disclosed the
agreement to the media, the National Liberation Army announced a
suspension of the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Last week, with the help of an archbishops federation in
Germany and Colombia, the two sides met in Mein and agreed to
resume their talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
