<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: Business Confidence in China Unaffected by Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Despite the Asian economic crisis,
the majority of U.S. companies in China are still "cautiously
optimistic" about China's economic prospects, according to a
survey conducted by the American Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 percent of the 162 respondents said their business
plans in China remain unaffected by problems elsewhere in Asia,
and 33 percent plan to deal with Asia's financial crisis by
focusing more on doing business in China.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that U.S. companies in China depend on
good Sino-U.S. relations. Almost all 162 business executives who
responded to the survey cited Sino-U.S. relations as having
significant effects on their business in China. One-fourth of the
respondents said Sino-U.S. relations greatly affect their ability
to do business. And, overall, 93 percent reported at least
moderate effects.
</P>
<P>
In further indications of confidence, almost nine of 10
companies plan to expand their businesses in China in the next
3-to-5 years, while two of three said they believe the Chinese
business climate is improving despite financial downturns
elsewhere in Asia.
</P>
<P>
In addition, four of five plan to increase the number of their
Chinese employees; one in four plans to substantially increase the
number of local employees. Nearly half plan to keep the number of
expatriate employees working in China, while 31 percent plan to
increase the number of expatriate employees.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the changes in the past 20 years, Philip Carmichael,
vice chairman of the American Chamber of Commerce in China, said
the investment environment in China is gradually improving. He is
optimistic about prospects in China, though some difficulties
still exist in doing business in the country.
</P>
<P>
The American Chamber of Commerce has more than 1,100 corporate
and individual members in China and represents more than 500
U.S. companies doing business in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commercial Factors Plague China's "Sound of Music" Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Commercial factors continue to
threaten the success of the Chinese production of "The Sound Of
Music," despite the outstanding artistic quality, according to a
recent issue of China Management News.
</P>
<P>
Chinese artists Wang Gang and wife, Cheng Fangyuan, reportedly
gambled their fortunes to produce Chinese version of the "The
Sound of Music" for the enjoyment of their curious and
enthusiastic countrymen. However, the publications reported that
the intended beneficiaries of the play have complained about the
poor commercial quality of the production.
</P>
<P>
Cheng, who previously abandoned her career as a singer to study
music in the United States, returned home to introduce the musical
to the Chinese audiences. However, the producers were unable to
find a suitable agency to administer related commercial affairs
due to the lack of familiarity with the western art
form. Consequently, the couple were forced to assume the role of
an agent.
</P>
<P>
"I'm only an artist, and know little about business," said
Wang. "We can only offer estimated figures for the income and
expenditures involved for each performance."
</P>
<P>
The debut performance in Beijing was a hit despite rumors of
financial problems. The success was followed by invitations to
appear in Shanghai, Nanjing, Shenzhen, Zhuhai and various other
cities, a fact which the newspaper reported as being a major
headache for the artists involved.
</P>
<P>
The publication clarified the statement, however, by noting
that the production team surveyed the minute details of
transporting and determined the need for ten trucks to carry props.
</P>
<P>
Wang, a host for China Central Television, expressed his
amazement that the musical was staged 1,400 time on Broadway, but
noted that the level of success depends extensive promotions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
