<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prodi Threatens to Step Down Unless Partners Reach Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
on Monday threatened to resign if talks between the parties in his
parliamentary coalition fail to agree on a policy platform for the
next year.
</P>
<P>
The Prodi government almost collapsed last week when the
Communist Refoundation party, whose votes give it a majority in
the Lower House, voted against NATO enlargement. The government
only survived thanks to the support of the centrist UDR party,
which is not part of the ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
Now the government has given itself a week to reach an accord
with Communist Refoundation on the main outline of its policies
for the next year and thus to avoid a repeat of last week's
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
Prodi, who wants to avoid fresh elections, stressed what was
needed was a "serious, thorough discussion to produce a government
which would last," according to the ANSA news agency.
</P>
<P>
Despite wanting to keep his government alive, Prodi has
repeatedly said he will not lead any other coalition than the
present one. His resignation would open the way for snap
elections.
</P>
<P>
"The country needs to continue along the line we have followed
in the last two years," he continued. "Italians need to know what
our policies will be up to the end of this legislature."
</P>
<P>
In order to reach an agreement which would keep Prodi in
office, the government will have to overcome serious differences
with Communist Refoundation. Among the contested issues are how
to tackle unemployment and boost the economy in the depressed
south and whether Italy should allow NATO to use its airbases for
possible air strikes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Communist Refoundation leader Fausto Bertinotti insists that he
is not afraid of going to elections immediately and appears ready
to bring the government down if he does not get his way.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very worried," he said Monday, when asked about the
chances of reaching an accord during the week of meetings which
began Monday.
</P>
<P>
"It depends essentially on the government's ability to take a
reformist turn," he said, shortly before meeting his party's
leadership to hammer out a common stance for the coming days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
