<HEADLINE> U.S., South Korea to Discuss Easing Sanctions on DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The United States and South
Korea will discuss how to ease U.S. sanctions on the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) as South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung had proposed, the State Department said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The working-level meeting will be held in Honolulu on July
13-15, and officials from both countries will "discuss further
this issue," a State Department spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Kim, during a visit to the United States last month, appealed
to U.S. President Bill Clinton to ease the U.S. sanctions against
the DPRK as a way to stabilize the situation on the Korean
Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the U.S. delegation was expected to be led
by Deputy Assistant Secretary of State Charles Kartman, and
would also include officials of the National Security Council and
the Defense Department.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean team would be headed by Kwon Jong-rak,
director-general for North American affairs at the South Korean
Foreign Ministry, he said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said they did not expect the meeting to lift
sanctions at least right now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
