<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Decides to Extend Mandate of MONUA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of the
United Nations Monday decided to extend the mandate of the United
Nations Observer Mission in Angola (MONUA) for a further period
until August 15 1998.
</P>
<P>
The council also decided to resume the withdrawal of the
military component of the MONUA in accordance with Resolution 1164
adopted by the Security Council on April 29, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The council reiterated its demand that the opposition party of
Angola UNITA immediately stop any attacks by its members on the
personnel of the MONUA, international personnel, the authorities
of the Government of Unity and National Reconciliation (GURN),
including the police and the civilian population.
</P>
<P>
The council called on the two sides and in particular UNITA to
guarantee unconditionally the safety and freedom of movement of
all United Nations and international personnel.
</P>
<P>
The council demanded that the GURN and in particular UNITA
cooperate fully with the MONUA in providing all access for its
verification activities.
</P>
<P>
The council requested the secretary-general to submit a report
no later than August 7, 1998 with recommendations regarding the
United Nations involvement in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Before adopting the resolution which decided to extend the
mandate of the MONUA, the Security Council paid respect by
observing silence to Alioune Blondin Beye, the U.N.
secretary-general's special envoy in Angola, who died when his
plane crashed near Abijan Friday night.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Deputy-Secretary-General Freshette Louise made a statement
at the Security Council, saying Beye is a man totally dedicated to
his mission, and a man no one can replace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
