<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Three-Year ESAF Credit for Kirgizstan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) announced here Monday the approval of a new three-year
credit for Kirgizstan under the Enhanced Structural Adjustment
Facility (ESAF), in an amount of about 86 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The concessional credit will be used to support the
government's economic program for 1998-2000. The first annual
loan, equivalent to about 29 million dollars, is available in two
equal semiannual installments, the first of which is available
immediately.
</P>
<P>
The new three-year program backed by the ESAF aims at a steady
output growth, a permanent reduction in inflation to single-digit
levels, and a strengthening of the external position. Fiscal
tightening and retrenchment will be the centerpiece of the
program.
</P>
<P>
The economic program for 1998 and 1999 is targeted at real GDP
growth of about 6 percent and 4.6 percent, respectively,
end-of-period inflation of 12 percent and 8 percent, respectively,
and an external current account deficit of about 7.5 percent of
GDP and 6.9 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Kirgiz Republic joined the IMF in May, 1992. Its quota is
about 86 million dollars and its outstanding use of IMF financing
currently totals 157 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Conference Begins on Combating Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Romania is open to cooperation
of any kind, apt to contribute to combating drug trafficking and
abuse, stressed Romanian President Emil Constantinescu in a
message addressed Monday to a regional conference on combating
drug smuggling and consumption, held in Bucharest.
</P>
<P>
He said that Romania wishes to closely correlate its foreign
policy with the international efforts aimed at achieving a
security architecture in its zone.
</P>
<P>
The message added that the changes that took place in the
South-East European countries after 1989 have enlarged cooperation
at various levels increased the risk of cross-border organized
crime, with drug production, trafficking and illegal intake as a
component playing a negative but very active role.
</P>
<P>
Constantinescu called for cooperation to diminish this world
scourge by exchanging information, taking tangible actions,
training specialists and supplying adequate means to fight
organized crime.
</P>
<P>
The regional conference on combating drug smuggling and
consumption started Monday in Bucharest, the conference attended
by officials from similar institutions in Bulgaria, Greece,
Turkey, Hungary, Ukraine, Moldova, as well as of the International
Criminal Police Organization (Interpol), the U.S. Justice
Department and the U.N. Program on Drugs Control.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Romanian Anti-Corruption and Organized Crime
Brigade Calin Mateescu said Romania represented a quasi-obligatory
transiting area for drugs smugglers and its police forces and
customs officers had detected and confiscated over 20 tons of
various illegal drugs in the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
As a result, he added, 480 criminal investigations were started
to involve 733 smugglers, out of whom 463 were foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Mateescu also said Romania had signed 57 accords, cooperation
agreements and implementation protocols with 29 European
countries, countries of the former Soviet Union, Latin America and
Eastern Asia, and was currently negotiating on the signing of such
agreements with another 33 countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
