<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At Least 19 Feared Killed in Storms, Floods in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- At least 19 people were killed
or missing from Minnesota to New England due to storms and floods
during the weekend in the Untied States.
</P>
<P>
In West Virginia, heavy rains overnight flooded streets and
some houses. A 4-year-old baby was swept from his mother's arms
and a blind man in a wheelchair was washed off his porch, in Frame
of the state. Neither of them was found.
</P>
<P>
In Bridgewater, New Hampshire, a man died after being sucked
into a narrow culvert.
</P>
<P>
Lightning strikes killed a Baltimore girl, a camper in upstate
New York, an Ohio teenager who was setting up a tent and a
Minnesota farmer holding a pitchfork.
</P>
<P>
Raging rivers swept away and killed two in New York and a woman
in Minnesota; the woman's husband was missing and presumed
drowned.
</P>
<P>
In Ohio, six people were killed in floods and a seventh died
when her mobile home was blown from its foundation.
</P>
<P>
A 35-year-old man was missing after his boat stalled and
plunged over a rain-swollen dam Saturday on Lake Arbutus,
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
Flash flooding caused by heavy rains and storms with high winds
forced hundreds fleeing their homes, closed roads and cut power to
more than 91,000 customers across West Virginia, prompting
Governor Cecil Underwood to declare a state of emergency in 17
counties.
</P>
<P>
In Wisconsin and Ohio, 44,000 people were without power late
Sunday. Ohio Governor George Voinovich declared 18 counties
disaster areas.
</P>
<P>
Lightning, flooding rivers and creeks and fallen power lines
left several states with widespread power outages and road
problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
