<HEADLINE> Alderdice to Be First N.Irish Assembly Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Lord Alderdice is set to become the
first speaker of the new Northern Ireland Assembly just hours
after he quit as leader of the Alliance Party following 11 years
in the job.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland Secretary Bi yowlam announced the appointment
Monday, saying Lord Alderdice's "political and parliamentary
experience means that he is well suited to carry out this role."
</P>
<P>
He will be known officially as the Presiding Officer in the new
body which meets for the first time Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
One of the first tasks of the Assembly will be to decide if
they want Lord Alderdice to take on the position on a permanent
basis.
</P>
<P>
Alderdice's non-partisan Alliance Party draws support from both
the Protestant and Roman Catholic nationalist communities in the
province.
</P>
<P>
Alderdice said he was resigning as leader of the party because
he won only six seats in the 108-chamber instead of his goal of
between eight and 10, meaning it failed to win a seat in its
12-member cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Alderdice was a central figure in protracted peace talks that
created an accord which led to the elections and his decision
stunned politicians and commentators.
</P>
<P>
But he emphasized he would continue to represent Alliance in
the House of Lords, Britain's upper parliamentary tier, and as a
member of the new assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
