<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank, Britain Launch New Trust Fund for East Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank and the British
Government Monday signed an agreement that launches a 40 million
U.S. dollar ASEM Trust Fund to help Asian nations in financial
crisis cope with rising unemployment and poverty.
</P>
<P>
Britain will contribute more than 8.3 million dollars to the
fund, which was devised in early April at a meeting of ASEM, or
Asia-Europe Meetings, a periodic summit of leading Asian countries
and the 15 members of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed by Joken Vereker, the permanent secretary
of the United Kingdom's Department for International Development,
and the World Bank managing director, Sven Sandstrom, will provide
Asian countries with technical assistance and advice on
restructuring their financial sectors and other measures to deal
with the growing social problems caused by the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Seven Asian countries are currently eligible to receive help
from the new ASEM Fund: China, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, South Korea, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Britain, other leading EU contributors include
France, the European Commission, the Netherlands, Denmark,
Finland, Luxembourg and Sweden have also pledged to support the
fund. Interest has been expressed by Italy, Singapore and Spain.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the ASEM fund's initial endowment will be
35 to 40 million dollars. The fund's activities are scheduled to
run until December 31, 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Approves Loan for Technology Investments in Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank Monday announced the approval of a 14.2 million U.S. dollar
loan to Panama to enhance the competitive capacity of private
sector through investments in research and technology.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used to help establish a Fund for Technology
and Business Modernization to further the process of innovation
and competitiveness as well as a fund for research, development
and dissemination.
</P>
<P>
The National Innovation System, a network of institutions,
agents and policies for the generation, adaptation and
dissemination of new technologies for the economy, will be
strengthened, and 10 pilot information centers, kiosks equipped
with computers with public access to the Internet, will be
established as a resource for small businesses.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the program is some 24.9 million dollars.
Local counterpart will contribute total 10.7 million dollars for
the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
