<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Pakistan Hold "Constructive" Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott has held "constructive" talks with Pakistan Foreign
Secretary Shamshad Ahmed, the State Department said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The discussions were constructive on both of our countries's
concerns about nonproliferation and the general situation in South
Asia," spokesman Lee McClenny told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said the meeting was part of the strong U.S. interest in
keeping lines of communication open with both India and Pakistan,
particularly in the wake of the nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
"We don't wish to isolate either country," he added.
</P>
<P>
McClenny said the United States would continue to talk with
Pakistan and with India to try to lessen tensions in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to keep our channels of communication open," he
said. "AS long as we're having good communication, that's good
enough for us."
</P>
<P>
McClenny also said the United States would exempt sales of
wheat from sanctions, imposed upon India and Pakistan since their
nuclear tests last month, as "they would fall into the area of
humanitarian assistance." 
</P>
</TEXT>
