<HEADLINE> Netherlands Beat Yugoslavia 2-1 in Thrillering Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
TOULOUSE, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands and Yugoslavia
played an exciting and classic World Cup game and the Dutch
prevailed 2-1 in the last minutes.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch team enjoyed a total advantage in the first half when
the Yugoslavians were not aggressive enough and let the Netherlands
take control of the midfield.
</P>
<P>
Striker Dennis Bergkamp nearly broke the deadlock at the 22nd
minute but his shot was punched out by Yugoslav goal-keeper Ivica
Kralj.
</P>
<P>
Kralj continued to display his splendid saves in the match but
Bergkamp tested him again at the 38th minute and this time the Dutch
striker succeeded with a right-footer to put the Netherlands 1-0 ahead.
</P>
<P>
The first 20 minutes of the second half saw a different story. The
Yugoslav team came back into the match strongly and Slobodan
Komljenovic headed home a free-kick from Dragan Stojkovic at the
48th minute.
</P>
<P>
Three minutes later, Vladimir Jugovic created another scoring chance
for the Yugoslav team when he was fouled by Dutch defender Jaap Stam
and got awarded a penalty shot.
</P>
<P>
But star midfielder Predrag Mijatovic shot the ball to crossbar.
It was the first missed penalty shot in the France'98 World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch team were obviously relieved by the narrow escape and
built up their confidence again. As the Yugoslavians getting more
tired in the last 15 minutes, the Dutch team resumed their advantage.
</P>
<P>
But the Yugoslavia team held on and managed to keep the 1-1
score to the last minutes of the match. Kralj put up another two
great saves but failed to block the third one -- a fierce left-foot
shot by Edgar Davids just out of the penalty area.
</P>
<P>
The goal was the last straw to the exhausted Yugoslavia team and
they could not even launch another attack after the goal.
</P>
<P>
The hard-fought victory put the Netherlands into the
quarter-finals. Their opponents will be the winners of the match
between Argentina and England at Saint-Etienne on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
