<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Appointed New COMESA Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Erastus Mwencha of Kenya has been
appointed as new Secretary-General of the Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA), Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba the outgoing COMESA Chairman, announced Monday in
Kinshasa, capital of the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said that the leaders attending the third COMESA
Summit in Kinshasa unanimously agreed Sunday night to appoint
Mwencha to replace Bingu Muthapika of Malawi, according to the
Pan-African News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Bingu was suspended in January 1997 for alleged impropriety at
the Lusaka COMESA Secretariat and later quitted.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha had been acting Secretary-General since the suspension
of Bingu.
</P>
<P>
After the announcement of his appointment, Mwencha said: "I
feel humbled that the countries have invested in me such a
challenging task in spite of the so many people who are qualified
out there and maybe much better. I do not want to assume it is
an appointment that one would merit in any way."
</P>
<P>
He said immediate task will be to ensure that the organization
will establish a free trade area by the year 2000, in order to
guarantee the free movement of goods and services.
</P>
<P>
COMESA member countries have agreed to reduce customs tariffs
by 90 percent in October this year and 100 percent by October
2000 to achieve a zero rate. However, eight of the 20 member
countries have not yet implemented the decision.
</P>
<P>
"The tasks ahead is daunting for the region but one feels
compelled it has to be done. I have been in the job and I know
the challenges that COMESA faces," Mwencha said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
