<DOCNO> XIE19980630.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three-Century-Old London Tea Auction Closes Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- London's tea auction, one of the
oldest traditions in the financial city, closed Monday after
319-year history.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 tea brokers and onlookers crowded into a
conference room at the London Chamber of Commerce for an emotional
farewell at the auction of the last 400 tons of tea.
</P>
<P>
The 50-minute auction was a nostalgic occasion, but with many
of the lots on offer failing to sell it illustrated clearly
London's declining role as a tea auction center.
</P>
<P>
The auction has been overtaken by technology and the increasing
globalization of the tea market. Rival auctions have sprung up
around the world and more and more buyers are using new methods of
communication, such as the internet or fax, to trade tea.
</P>
<P>
Ever since 1,679 tea buyers have gathered on a weekly basis. By
the 1950s a third of all the world's tea was bought through the
auction.
</P>
<P>
But auctions have been in steady decline in recent decades.
This year they have been held every two weeks, due to lack of
volume. Now less than 8 percent of the tea drunk in Britain is
sold under the hammer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
